<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Should Be Protected: Pak PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said here Wednesday that the World Trade Organization (WTO)
must pay special attention to maximizing the trading potential of
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address at the Ninth Annual Corporate
Conference of the Asia Society which opened Wednesday evening at
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, Sharif said that
the new international economic regime must not only create a level
playing field but also protect the disadvantaged nations from any
form of exploitation.
</P>
<P>
"This is an age of interdependence. We expect that a spirit of
fair play and constructive competition will prevail in the new
trading regime," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Disparities in incomes between nations and among people are
startling, Sharif said. Unless this is redressed, global progress
and stability will remain a distant dream, he added
</P>
<P>
In this world of interdependence, however, an island of
prosperity cannot sustain itself in an ocean of poverty, Sharif
noted. Prosperity and peace must go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
"We must strive for an interdependent world if four-fifths of
humankind are to be saved from the deep abyss of poverty," the
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
On the recent financial crisis in Asia, Sharif said that the
roots of the crisis can be traced to the large flow of unregulated
and inadequately reported flow of private capital to the affected
counties going into imprudent lending to sectors like property or
services.
</P>
<P>
In other words, this was crisis stemming from the capital
account and not a current account deficit, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Viewed in this context, it will be appropriate to call this a
crisis of global financial management and not just an Asian
crisis, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The strategy for reinvigorating growth should focus on balanced
growth, on a wider dispersal of opportunities, and on securing the
integration of developing countries in the global market, Sharif
said.
</P>
<P>
This must be ensured by investment in their natural resources;
by expanding their infrastructure, especially the transport and
communication links; by developing their human resources; by
enhancing their productivity and efficiency; and by the
stimulation of demand, he added.
</P>
<P>
Priority should be given to assisting the developing countries
in their policies and programs of deregulation and liberalization,
in particular by safeguarding against likely adverse developments
in the transitional period, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Structural adjustment should be undertaken in the advanced
countries in order to stimulate demand for imports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Priorities should also be given to resisting new protectionist
tendencies especially those on environmental and social grounds;
and intensifying efforts for transfer and diffusion of technology
to the new power house economies, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The tremendous productive potential for reinvigorating world
growth has to be harnessed properly to avoid economic and social
dislocations on a large scale, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are indivisible and poverty anywhere is a
threat to prosperity everywhere, he said. "Ensuring world peace
and banishing poverty should therefore be high on our agenda,"
Sharif added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
