<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Not Prepared to Guarantee E-Commerce Tax Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government, fearing a
huge loss of potential income, is balking at a U.S. drive to
guarantee that Internet and global electronic commerce remain tax
free.
</P>
<P>
So far, Canada is one of the few countries that refuses to sign
on to the U.S. concept of not imposing duties or other taxes on
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
At a trade negotiators' meeting in Geneva last week, Canada
said it would only consider a four-year moratorium on taxing
Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
The government insists it has not yet made up its mind whether
it will tax Internet transactions. At present, only goods and
services tax is levied on Internet sales at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
Revenue Minister Herb Dhaliwal had said that his government
wanted to make sure tax laws are "appropriately applied" to
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
"The department wants to ensure the integrity of Canada's tax
base continues to be maintained," he was quoted as saying in
Wednesday's Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Canada's federal and provincial governments are also worried
that they will see their retail tax base quickly erode if Internet
sales remain tax free.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S., Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said
Tuesday that she had convinced most major countries not to impose
import duties or other taxes on Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
"We already have a critical mass of countries that agree with
the duty-free cyberspace concept," Barshefsky said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
