<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Holbrooke for Failed Trip in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday accused U.S
presidential envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke of not exerting
pressure upon the Turkish Cypriot side to break the present
impasse of the Cyprus problem
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Parliamentary Foreign Affairs Committee meeting,
Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yiannos Kranidiotis said that the
U.S. envoy's mistake was that he failed in exerting appropriate
pressure upon the Turkish Cypriot side and did not attribute
responsibility for the failure where it belonged.
</P>
<P>
He accused Holbrooke of maintaining "a policy of equal
distances."
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that Greece would launch an international
campaign to inform public opinion and governments about the Cyprus
problem and Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government Monday expressed its regret and
disappointment with the lack of progress in the protracted Cyprus
problem, saying that the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
should bear the responsibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
