<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister Visits Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
greeted Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi at the White House
Wednesday, but not mentioning the Marine jet accident that killed
20 skiers in the Italian Alps.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Prodi at the White House, Clinton first noted that
U.S. personnel from the Aviano air base were assisting in rescue
efforts after this week's storms in southern Italy and then
expressed thanks to Italians for their "hospitality toward United
States forces working to preserve peace in Europe."
</P>
<P>
"The history of our partnership is long and special; every
schoolchild knows that Columbus crossed the Atlantic in 1492,"
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"That was only the beginning of a relationship that has now
flourished for centuries bringing us together in new ways
generation after generation," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his own remarks, from a reviewing stand on the South Lawn,
Prodi called their two nations "two citizens of the next
millennium bound by common values."
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he wanted to pursue a "vast sphere of free trade"
between the U.S. and Europe "not only to best utilize our energy
and to strengthen as much as possible our political and economic
ties but also as a common contribution to the global trade
liberalization."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters before
Prodi's arrival that Clinton would have nothing more direct to say
in public about the Marines' incident because the case was before
a military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said Clinton was hoping privately to
assuage any remaining sore feelings among the Italian people, and
was anxious to see how Prodi will respond.
</P>
<P>
"This has been a subject of enormous concern and pain to both
of our governments," McCurry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We just need to see how they address it. I think we have dealt
with this in a sensitive way and in a way that is designed to
ensure that justice is done," the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
As Prodi arrived, a military court in Camp LeJeune, N.C., began
hearings into whether two crewmen should be court-martialed over
the Feb. 3 accident involving a low-flying Marine jet from the
U.S. air base in Aviano.
</P>
<P>
Following the accident, angry Italians decried American pilots
as careless "Rambos" and Communist leaders demanded the closure of
U.S. military bases in their country. Clinton phoned Prodi and
promised a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Clinton also wanted to discuss the summit
of industrialized nations next week in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
Prodi arrived here on Tuesday for his first visit to the U.S.
as the prime minister of Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
