<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Efforts for African Timber Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Agriculture and
Rural Development Carlos Fernandes said here Wednesday that his
country has made "positive contributions" to the stable
development of Africa's timber industry since May 1996.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the two-year period during which Angola
has been the chairman country of the African Timber Organization
(ATO).
</P>
<P>
The minister told the press here in the Luanda Airport before
departing for the 18th ATO meeting to be held in Bangui, capital
of the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Fernandes said, Angola has done much
publicity work advocating rational development of forest
resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it also pressed for the industrialization of timber
exploitation among ATO member states so as to enhance the
capability of timber processing, which has increased both timber
export and job opportunities for the members.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes believed that these measures are in the interests of
all ATO member countries.
</P>
<P>
On the forthcoming ATO meeting, the minister said, it will
mainly discuss issues concerning ATO's cooperation with other
relevant international or regional organizations, as well as
membership applications by Mali, Senegal, Benin, Guinea and Togo.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1976, the ATO now has 13 members comprising Angola,
Tanzania, Liberia, Central African Republic, Cameroon, Nigeria,
the Democratic Republic of Congo, Congo Republic, Cote d'Ivoire,
Gabon, Ghana, Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, and Equatorial Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Its goal is to coordinate policies on the protection and
utilization of forest resources among the member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
