<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Truth Body Sends out Reparation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has sent reparation notices to
the first 700 people officially declared victims of gross human
rights violations, the TRC said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu said the victims have been informed
that they were eligible to apply for reparations, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The TRC's reparations and rehabilitation committee receives
applications for reparation and decides who are victims of gross
human right violations eligible to apply for reparation.
</P>
<P>
Interim reparations are once-off payments, normally a maximum
of 2,000 Rand (400 U.S. Dollars), for victims who had suffered
hardship in the apartheid era and were in need, or their
dependants.
</P>
<P>
"For us it is a tremendous, historic day. It is almost like we
are beginning our work," Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
The commission had spent two years collecting statements,
hearing public testimonies and individually corroborating each of
the more than 20,000 statements received.
</P>
<P>
If a victim had suffered hardship and was in particular need,
the reparations committee would forward the application to the
president's fund, the body set up to make reparations payments.
</P>
<P>
A TRC staff member said that the amount of reparations could
be increased on a sliding scale if the conditions of the victims
and their dependants warranted it.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said the findings in a minority of cases, where people
had been found not to be victims of gross human rights
violations, would also be sent out soon.
</P>
<P>
These people would be able to appeal against the decision, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The truth body is scheduled to end its work on June 30 and a
final report on its findings will be produced at that time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
