<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's First Satellite Rotating Normally in Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Information
Safwat el-Sherif said Wednesday that the country's first satellite
Nilesat 101 is now rotating in its pre-set orbit in outer space.
</P>
<P>
Nilesat will rotate in this orbit for the duration of its
presumed 16-year life span following its successful launching by
the Ariane-4 Rocket from the Korou air space in French Guyana,
South America on April 28.
</P>
<P>
Nilesat 101 is being tracked by five ground stations in Egypt,
France, South America and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters that Nilesat is now rotating in a
regular manner at a distance of 36,000 kilometers from earth.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Egyptian Radio and Television Union Abdel
Rahman Hafez said there is a clear contact between the satellite
and the main ground station at Six of October City, about 30
kilometers southeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The timetable for synchronizing, correcting, tests, operation,
measuring capacity and ground coverage will complete by the end of
May, in time for Media Day on May 31.
</P>
<P>
On Media Day, the official celebration of operating the Nilesat
will take place, when President Hosni Mubarak will give the signal
to place television and radio programs on the satellite for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
There will be 50 general and specialized television channels,
open and encrypted, to be viewed by Egyptians and Arabs by the use
of small, low-cost dishes, Hafez said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has already signed contracts with Libya and Oman to lease
its space channels on the satellite. A space channel is expected
to be leased to Lebanon shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
