<HEADLINE> Swaziland to Have First Passenger Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland, the tiny southern
African kingdom, will have its first passenger train service next
week, South African Press Association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A twice-weekly service will start on May 12 from Mpaka,
Swaziland to Durban, a busy seaport in South Africa, and from
Mpaka to Mozambique's capital, Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The service has been jointly organized by Swaziland Railways,
South Africa's state-owned railway company Spoornet and their
Mozambican counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Sleeping arrangements on the train will be provided with
adequate security, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The fare of the 20-hour journey from Durban to Maputo will be
152 Rand (about 30 U.S. Dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
