<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Base Minerals Depressed in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's base minerals have
remained depressed in the first quarter of this year as a result
of low demand mainly from Asia where there has been a financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the performance of the financial sector during the
first quarter of the year, the Zimbabwe Financial Holdings
(Finhold) said a number of mining companies continued to close
down, especially gold mining companies, as operating costs rose
following the plunge of local currency last November, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, those mining companies which managed to increase
export volumes benefited somewhat from the weaker Zimbabwean
Dollar, as profitability in local currency terms improved.
</P>
<P>
"Among others, in the short term, copper prices are not
expected to recover from their recent low due to the fact that
the copper market is likely to remain in surplus by about 300,000
tons in 1998," Finhold said.
</P>
<P>
Nickel, which fell by 2.1 percent on the last quarter of 1997
to 5,310 U.S. Dollars per ton in the first quarter of 1998, was
likely to decline further to about 5,100 U.S. Dollars per ton in
the short to medium-term.
</P>
<P>
However, minerals like platinum and gold had shown some
improvement during the first three months of the year, with
platinum prices rising by 13.3 percent in January to 412 U.S.
Dollars per ounce in March.
</P>
<P>
Also, in the first quarter of this year, the gold market
showed signs of recovery as reflected by the fact that the price
of gold rose slightly by 5.3 percent from 288 U.S. Dollars per
ounce in January to 303 U.S. Dollars per ounce in March.
</P>
<P>
"In the short to medium-term, the price of gold is expected to
remain generally stable at around 315 U.S. Dollars per ounce as
supplies are expected to decline at a faster rate than demand,"
said Finhold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
