<HEADLINE> Canadian Auto Sales Up 3.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Canadian auto sales were up 3.4
percent to 137,050 units in April from a year earlier, even though
many consumers adopted a wait-to-buy attitude for more incentives
from automakers.
</P>
<P>
General Motors of Canada Ltd. saw its sales slip 5.9 percent to
40,846 units, led by a 10.1 percent decline in passenger car
sales, reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Overall sales at Ford Motor Co. of Canada Ltd. fell 4.8 percent
to 28,121 units, driven down by a 14.5 percent decline in
passenger car sales. Its light truck sales rose 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Canada Ltd. was the only one of the Big Three
automakers that recorded a sale rise in April.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler's monthly sales edged up 2.1 percent to 24.806 units.
But the record April sales of light trucks were offset by a 20.4
percent fall in car sales.
</P>
<P>
In April, Toyota Canada Inc. had its best month on record, with
a gain of 42 percent. Its total sales reached 13,562 units.
</P>
</TEXT>
