<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus: No Trouble in Ties With Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Wednesday rejected the
allegation that its ally Greece is intended to improve ties with
Turkey, which still controls a third of the island's territory.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
hailed the Cyprus-Greece cooperation as "perfect" and praised
Greeks' policy on the Cyprus question.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as a reaction to the criticism by House
President Spyros Kyprianou against the Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis that he subscribes to U.S. policy with regard to improving
relations with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
There is "no reason to question either the intentions or the
moves the Greek government makes in connection with the Cyprus
problem," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government is "fully briefed" about the Greeks'
moves towards the Cyprus issue which are "in the framework of the
common strategy."
</P>
<P>
The two governments agreed on a joint defense pact in 1993,
under which Greece will provide military assistance to Cyprus in
case it is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Greece, together with Turkey and Britain were guarantors of
Cyprus' independence under the 1960 Treaty of Establishment of
the Cyprus Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
