<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Warring Parties Agree on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese warring sides
Wednesday reached an agreement on the recognition of the right of
self-determination for the people of southern Sudan and agreed to
continue to seek a negotiated settlement to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here on Wednesday at the
end of a three-day Sudanese peace talks, Kenyan Foreign Minister
Bonaya Godana said that there is a "limited progress" at the
second round of the peace talks between the Sudanese government
and the Sudanese People's Liberation Movement (SPLM).
</P>
<P>
He noted that limited progress was made in terms of the
government's acceptance of self-determination right for the
people in Southern Sudan but the progress was "not too
optimistic".
</P>
<P>
Attending the three-day peace talks opened on May 4 are the
Sudanese government delegation led by Foreign Minister Mustafa
Osman and the SPLM delegation headed by Nhial Deng, Governor of
southern Bahr el Ghazal Province.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued by the IGAD (Inter-Governmental
Authority for Development) Ministerial Sub-Committee Meeting on
the South Sudan Conflict, the minister said that the right of
self-determination would be exercised through an internationally
supervised referendum at the end of an interim period.
</P>
<P>
The interim arrangement is to be negotiated and agreed upon by
the two parties through the IGAD peace process, said the Kenyan
minister who opened the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
According to Godana, the two parties to the conflict in
Southern Sudan were unable to reach a common ground on the
question of state and religion.
</P>
<P>
During the first round of peace talks held here last October,
the two parties could not agree on two issues, namely, the right
of self-determination for the people of southern Sudan and the
relationship between state and religion.
</P>
<P>
At the IGAD Ministerial Sub-Committee Meeting held here
between May 4 and 6, Godana said that the IGAD sub-committee
agreed to undertake shuttle diplomacy as a means of narrowing the
gap between the two parties on outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
On the humanitarian assistance to southern Sudan affected by
famine, The Sudanese government offered a ceasefire and immediate
stop of hostilities to facilitate the unhindered flow of relief
supply, while the SPLM declared that unhindered relief assistance
to the needy should not be linked to a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Referring to differences on the definition of southern Sudan,
Godana said that the SPLM required to plus Abyei, Southern
Kordofan and Southern Blue Nile in addition to three provinces of
Bahr el Ghazal, Equatoria and Upper Nile accepted by the Sudanese
government as southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The two warring parties agreed at the talks to convene the
third round of peace talks in three months time in Addis Ababa,
capital of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Sub-Committee meeting was attended by foreign ministers of
Ethiopia, Eritrea and Uganda, representative of current IGAD
Chairman Ahmed Issa Gabobeh and IGAD official Kinfe Abraham under
the chairmanship of Kenyan foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in southern Sudan broke out in 1983 between the
Moslem-ruled Khartoum government in the north and the SPLM
fighting for more autonomy and religious freedom in the animist
and Christian-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 1.3 million Sudanese have reportedly been
killed during the past 15 years by the conflicts between the two
parties and natural calamities in southern Sudan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
