<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Financial Crisis Tops G-15 Summit Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The three-day G-15 summit which will
open here Monday will flesh out ways to deal with the financial
crisis in southeast Asia and to avoid a repetition elsewhere in
future, Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Seven heads of state, three vice presidents and a number of
ministers will attend the eighth summit of the group of 16
developing countries, in which they will issue a communique
spelling out the group's stances on economic and political issues.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial turbulence will be among several main axes
of the communique to be issued at the end of the annual summit,
MENA quoted the draft document as saying.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting of the G-15 foreign ministers Saturday,
Malaysia will present a report outlining its viewpoint on the
financial crisis and lessons drawn from it in order to avoid a
repetition.
</P>
<P>
The draft final communique will also outline ways of
strengthening South-South cooperation and at the same time
activating constructive North-South dialog.
</P>
<P>
It will call for easing the burdens of debts of developing
countries in general and the G-15 countries in particular and ask
the international community to offer effective solutions to this
problem.
</P>
<P>
Mounir Zahran, Egypt's permanent delegate at the U.N. European
headquarters in Geneva expected the signing during the Cairo
summit of an agreement to set up a union of chambers of commerce to
promote trade exchange among G-15 countries.
</P>
<P>
Inter-trade exchange among G-15 countries represented about 9
percent of their overall trade volume which amounted to about
796 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"A new mechanism, a union of chambers of commerce, was required
to promote trade, strengthen relations among businessmen and
remove trade obstacles among them," Zahran said.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia will propose the launching of a technology
data project to activate trade exchange and industrial
cooperation. The proposal will be presented to a meeting of the
G-15 ministers of trade on Friday.
</P>
<P>
India will present a report on the obstacles to trade exchange
between developing and advanced countries and to the flow of G-15
trade to world markets.
</P>
<P>
As a group of developing countries from Latin America, Africa
and Asia, the G-15 was founded in 1989. Kenya became the 16th
member last year, joining Egypt, India, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Algeria, Zimbabwe, Senegal, Nigeria, Argentina, Jamaica,
Venezuela, Mexico, Brazil, Peru and Chile.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members, accounting for 30 percent of the world's
population and 27 percent of land area, represent the emerging
economies of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
Their total gross domestic product makes up 39 percent of the
third world and exports, 31 percent of the developing countries'
total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Decides to Expand Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A meeting on the involvement of
Angola's private sector in infrastructure construction was
concluded here Wednesday, with a resolution to expand the
country's privatization so as to restore the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, jointly sponsored by the Angolan Ministry of
Economic Planning and the World Bank, resolved to revise laws
concerning economic sections under state monopoly, and to allow
the participation of private sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the meeting, telecommunications, transport and
road, health infrastructure, energy and water are now among the
priorities opened for the privatization.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting agreed that the resolution will
invite remarkable changes in the structure of Angola's strategic
departments and ensure faster restoration of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1998-2000 economic rehabilitation program of the
Angolan government, the privatization will be realized through
open tender.
</P>
<P>
However, the government delegates stressed at the meeting that
priority should be offered to national enterprises for
infrastructure privatization.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Tanzania and Bolivia shared their
experiences in privatization at the meeting, which was opened
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
