<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Proposes U.N. Debate on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia will bring back before the
U.N. Security Council its proposal to discuss ways of supporting
U.N. secretary-general's good offices mission in Cyprus, a Russian
diplomat said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides, Russian ambassador Georgi Mouradov said before
U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard Holbrooke's visit to the island
a few days earlier, "the U.S. had requested we cancel the debate
at the Security Council until after a visit here by Richard
Holbrooke and we had agreed."
</P>
<P>
Following Holbrooke's visit to Nicosia, which ended on Monday,
Moscow "will bring back the same proposal as the visit's results
make a debate necessary," the Russian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke had three days of extensive consultations with the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, but failed to get them back
to the negotiating table as Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
insisted on the recognition of his self-styled regime in northern
Cyprus and the withdrawal of Cyprus' application to join the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on Russia's proposal, Mouradov said it aims to back
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's good offices mission, the
bicommunal dialog between the two sides and to support Annan's
special advisor for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, who chaired two rounds of peace talks between
Clerides and Denktash last summer, is expected to visit the island
soon, said Mouradov.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to cooperate with all Security Council
permanent member states to solve the Cyprus question and facts
have proven that joint efforts could be more productive, instead
of isolated efforts by any country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Denktash's preconditions, Mouradov said Russia
supports the continuation of the dialog between the leaders of
the two communities and all U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Denktash, angered by European Union's decision to open accession
talks with Cyprus, walked out of peace talks with Clerides.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the divided
island in a bizonal, bicommunal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
