<HEADLINE> LIFFE to Launch Innovative Futures Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) - The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) announced Wednesday it would
introduce a series of contracts called LIFFE Libor Financed Bonds.
</P>
<P>
The new Bonds will replicate the interest rate and price
sensitivity of interest rate swaps, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Initially the contracts will be denominated in deutschmarks
with the provision to convert to the euro at the start of Economic
and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The first of these contracts will be positioned at the 5 and 10
year areas of the swaps curve and will be launched in the fourth
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The LIFFE Libor Financed Bond adopts a pricing mechanism that
ensures that its price performance replicates the price
sensitivity of an interest rate swap.
</P>
<P>
The contract can be considered similar to a cash settled bond
futures contract with only one bond in the deliverable basket.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Hodson, Chief Exekcutive of LIFFE, said: "This
initiative reflects the increased efficiency and enormous growth
of the swaps market."
</P>
<P>
"It also recognizes market expectation that the euro-swap curve
will become the benchmark for the European fixed income markets,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Airports Suffer Worst Delay in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) - Delay as Britain's six largest
airports increased last year to their highest level since 1991,
the Financial Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) as saying the
average delay was 16 minutes, compared with 14 minutes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, flights were delayed by an average of 20 minutes and
by 18 minutes in 1991. The figures are averages of all flights
from the airports and not just of those that were delayed.
</P>
<P>
The CAA said last year's performance was still better than in
the late 1980s, in spite of a 24 percent increase in the number of
flights since then.
</P>
<P>
Last year's delays had a variety of causes, including weather,
industrial action, air traffic control difficulties, defective
aircraft, missing passengers and security hold-ups.
</P>
<P>
International flights were delayed more often than domestic
services. Delays were also more likely on long-haul routes than on
short-haul flights.
</P>
<P>
According to the CAA, the worst airports for scheduled
passengers were all in London. Delays at Gatwick and Luton
airports averaged 16 minutes. At Healthrow, the average delay was
14 minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
