<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Discusses Head-quarter Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The long-expected NATO internal
adaptation has moved from blueprint to materialization as the
alliance's chiefs of staff met for two days to launch
restructuring discussion, though tentative and initial.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chiefs of staff dealt with the issue of how many and
who man which position in the future 20 regional head-quarters at
their meeting that concluded on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision taken at last December's NATO council meeting of
defense ministers has slashed regional head-quarters from 65 down
to 20 whereas the planned inclusion of Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic complicates the issue.
</P>
<P>
NATO decided last December that the principle of rotation
between countries for key commanding posts would be applied and
that 50 percent of the posts of a head-quarter should be allocated
to foreign nationals to guarantee a multinational character of
inter-allied staff headquarters.
</P>
<P>
General Klaus Naumann, chairman of the NATO Military Committee,
said that the three invitees should be included in the
head-quarters and for precise jobs.
</P>
<P>
The general told the press that the discussion was just like,
to use military terminology, the first shot to help train in later
rounds of shells. Wednesday's discussion was to seek views from
member states, the general added.
</P>
<P>
The military committee, the highest military authority within
the western alliance, had to be cautious for NATO had failed its
internal adaptation attempt the first time in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs of staff adopted, according to the military
committee chairman, a basic document concerning the internal
adaptation and agreed on an outline implementation plan that
demands that the internal adaptation should be achieved no later
than April 1999 by means of simultaneous activation of the
regional headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The outline implementation plan will be submitted by the
military committee to the autumn meeting of NATO defense ministers
for approval.
</P>
<P>
A tricky issue remained as how to maintain the military
hierarchy and balance the national and NATO responsibilities
through the appointment of generals with different numbers of
stars.
</P>
<P>
Naumann described the issue as both interesting and
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chiefs of staff also met their counterparts from the
three invitees, Russia, Ukraine and from the 28 Partnership for
Peace member countries.
</P>
<P>
A broad range of issues were dealt with during these meetings,
including the current situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, the
follow-on force to replace SFOR, the interoperability of NATO
integration, the defense of air space for the three invitee
countries and the trials of the Combined Joint Task Forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
