<HEADLINE> Martyrs' Day Marked in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 30,000 Lebanese, mostly
students, gathered in the Martyr Square here on Wednesday to mark
the Martyrs' Day, commemorating those who sacrificed for the
country's independence and liberation.
</P>
<P>
The move came as fighters of the Hezbollah, or Party of God,
are leading a guerrilla war against Israeli occupation of south
Lebanon. Many fighters of the Hezbollah and other resistance
forces have been killed in clashes with Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the gathering, Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri
reiterated Lebanon's rejection of Israel's withdrawal offer,
saying the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 can not be
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a border strip in south Lebanon to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Due to heavy casualties that the Israeli troops have been
suffering, the Israeli government has decided to withdraw from
Lebanon under the condition that security arrangements be
negotiated with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, insisting that the withdrawal
be unconditional under the U.N. resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will never hold talks with the Jewish state over this
issue, Hariri said. He demanded Israel withdraw its troops
immediately and unconditionally from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the role of the young people, he said that his
government will give priority to them and the whole society should
consult with them over the nation's development and future.
</P>
