<HEADLINE> Tiny Gun Calls Interpol's Attention: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A key-fob-like gun with the killing
capacity has been found in several world airports, emphasizing the
need for international cooperation to check such a new weapon,
according to the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The pistol is three inches long and an inch wide, which can
fire two shots of 0.32-caliber bullets and it would be deadly from
a distance of up to 20 yards, the paper quoted an official of the
Interpol, the international police agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Such pistols have been confiscated at airports in Australia,
Britain and Greece, with the first ones seized in Perth last
September and the latest case in Athens last Wednesday, the Times
said.
</P>
<P>
The Lyon, France-based Interpol has alerted its 177 members
around the world on the weapon's emergence, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
