<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Urges Cut Down on Public Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Wednesday called for reduction of public expenditure to ease the
financial pressure on the government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an economic consultative meeting held here, the
president said that the reduction would "enable us to lower the
tax burden on the private sector, thus encouraging firms to make
the investment that is necessary for Kenya's growth."
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that over the past decade, the government had to
increase short-term domestic borrowing by six fold in order to
finance the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
According to a working paper distributed at the meeting,
Kenya's domestic debt has more than doubled from 63 billion
Kenyan Shillings (about 1.05 billion U.S. Dollars) in 1992 to 150
billion Shillings (about 2.5 billion Dollars) at present.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that over 25 percent of all public
expenditure was required to meet the interest on government
domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
He said that interest payment for domestic debt, and salaries
and allowances for civil servants and teachers would consume more
than 80 percent of total public expenditure, leaving few
resources for capital investment.
</P>
<P>
Moi told the one-day meeting, which was attended by government
ministers, members of parliament from both ruling and opposition
parties, diplomats and officials from the World Bank and other
international bodies, that the Ministry of Finance had already
instructed all ministries to review their activities and
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
He urged the meeting to make specific proposals on reducing
the share of public expenditures relative to gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, President Moi called for unity among Kenyan
people, saying that "if we throw our peace out of the window,
there is no development that can take place in this country."
</P>
<P>
The working paper prepared by a team of advisors said that
domestic debt had become a serious structural constraint to the
achievement of rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The current high levels of interest rates on bank lending
ranging from 30 percent to 40 percent have drastically
discouraged economic growth since the private sector cannot
afford to borrow money at such high interest rates, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
The team appointed by President Moi on April 30 noted that
bold measures should be urgently taken to deal particularly with
the high domestic debt and interest rates problems.
</P>
<P>
According to the working paper, the current level of
corruption in the East African country is adversely affecting
efficiency and effectiveness of government policy and operations.
</P>
<P>
During the discussions, Kimani Wanyoike, Chairman of the
opposition Ford People, pointed out that political will on the
government side and security provided by the state machinery were
the prerequisite in solving the current economic problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
