<HEADLINE> Egypt: Peace Progress Hinges on Accepting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The success of the coming Washington
peace talks depends on the acceptance by the Palestinian and
Israeli sides of the U.S. proposal, Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have already accepted the American plan which
calls for a further Israeli withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank, while Israel has not to date announced its stance on
the issue, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day London talks that wrapped up Tuesday,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright set a deadline of next
Monday for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to accept the
U.S. initiative, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
If the Palestinians and Israelis accept the U.S. proposal,
Washington's leading role in the peace process will be clearly
demonstrated, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Progress can never be achieved without accepting all key
elements of the U.S. initiative and a further Israeli redeployment
before the final status negotiations begin," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Asked to assess steps taken in the peace process so far, Moussa
said that he cannot voice any optimism or pessimism until he meets
with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat here
Thursday and gets to know the Israeli stance which has not been
determined yet.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet will discuss the new U.S. initiative and
made a decision on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Albright is known seeking Israeli approval of a further
pullback of 13 percent from the West Bank, an interim withdrawal
proposal acceptable to Arafat but shunned by Netanyahu who has
offered no more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who started a tour of Morocco, Algeria and Tunisia
following the London talks Tuesday, will make a full assessment of
the peace process on the Palestinian-Israeli track with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
1997 over Israeli settlement construction and long-delayed
withdrawal from the West Bank. 
