<HEADLINE> WFP Accused Liberians of Looting Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) has been
complaining about the lack of security in Liberia as some of its
food donation to the country has been looted in two incidents.
</P>
<P>
A WFP regional manager said Wednesday that in the first
incident, a vehicle of WFP food was stopped at a check point when
entering a township in the capital Monrovia and the food loaded
was looted by soldiers of the Armed Forces of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The food was not returned despite the protest of officers of
the WFP and other international aid agencies, he said, quoted by
a British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The second incident took place on May 2 when a convoy truck
was stopped on the way to a northwestern town by a group of
citizens armed with knives.
</P>
<P>
"They stopped the vehicle and they proceeded to loot 32 tons
of food," the WFP manager said, adding that about 13 tons of the
food was reclaimed, with the balance still missing.
</P>
<P>
One of the WFP personnel was seriously injured in the
incident.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the incidents might be triggered
off by the poverty in these areas as a lot of people there have
no income, the country is being rehabilitated and the
agricultural sector is not producing much.
</P>
<P>
"These people are taking the food probably because they are
required to feed themselves or to generate some income from the
sale of it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has met the country's defense minister to protest and
asked him to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Although there are many problems in the country, he said, the
WFP hopes the government would ensure the security of relief
agencies like WFP to help the country rebuild itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
