<HEADLINE> Clinton Decides Temporary Cut to One Carrier in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton has
decided to cut its major naval force in the Gulf from two aircraft
carriers to one temporarily from late May as the situation in the
region has calmed down since the Iraqi crisis on weapons
inspections early this year, Pentagon officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The carrier Independence is scheduled to leave the waters for
the United States in late May, leaving the carrier John Stennis
there alone for about three weeks, maintaining the watch over
Iraq, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft carrier Eisenhower, originally scheduled to
replace the Independence on May 13, will remain in the naval port
Norfolk, Virginia, until June 10, they said.
</P>
<P>
The officials said Clinton made the decision on Tuesday to
remain one carrier temporarily in the region, and Defense
Secretary William Cohen then ordered the change.
</P>
<P>
there will be a "gap, a temporary gap" in the Gulf, a military
source said. "It means there will be one carrier in the Gulf for a
short time," he added.
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon spokesman stressed the plan could change and
additional forces could be added to the region if the situation in
the Gulf become troublesome.
</P>
<P>
"The president has made no final decision regarding force level
adjustments in the Arabian Gulf region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters the
president was considering cutting back on the dozens of warships
in the Gulf as "the conditions are somewhat less threatening than
when they were being built up."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is under mounting pressure from
Capitol Hill to slim the deployment, which lawmakers argue has
proven costly both financially and in troop morale.
</P>
<P>
A seven-senator delegation just back from a tour of overseas
outposts on Wednesday said they found the troop morale was
extremely low among U.S. forces sent to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
