<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Terms Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic growth
continued at a "moderate to strong" pace in March and April
throughout much of the country but some regions reported weaker
points, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's central bank noted in its "Beige Book" survey of
regional economic developments through early last week that
"expansion was occurring in nearly all districts, although Dallas
reported some signs of slowing growth amid basically strong
regional economic conditions and Minneapolis noted some weakening
of business activity."
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey report, named after the color of its cover, was
compiled from reports submitted by it's 12 district banks. It will
be used when Fed policy-makers sit down May 19 to determine
whether or not to raise short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
"despite increases in labor costs, business contacts indicated
that competitive pressures were holding prices in check for most
goods," it said.
</P>
<P>
Nationwidely, there were only two districts -- Dallas and San
Francisco, recorded increases in service prices.
</P>
<P>
"Labor markets continued to be tight," the report said. "There
was some evidence of increased wage pressures in service
industries and for computer and technical professionals."
</P>
<P>
Although the report had a generally upbeat tone, the
Minneapolis bank said "increasing weakness in farming and other
natural resource sectors is casting a pall over spending in rural
areas... (of) Montana, North Dakota and South Dakota."
</P>
<P>
The Dallas district bank said economic activity in its region
was slightly slower than at the start of the year. It said Asia
had weakened manufacturing and lower oil prices had caused "a
strong shift away from oil-directed drilling."
</P>
<P>
In general, the report found "generally robust" consumer
spending and increased factory production in a wide variety of
industries, especially in production of construction materials and
furniture and appliances.
</P>
<P>
However, it noted Asia-linked declines in production of
electronic items in the Boston district, chemicals in the St.
Louis, Dallas and Cleveland regions, metals in the Philadelphia
district and machinery in the Richmond district. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
