<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Urges N.Irish Voters to Say Yes to Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Wednesday urged all sides in Northern Ireland to vote "yes" in the
upcoming referendum on peace deal and isolate the paramilitary
gunmen who do not observe peace.
</P>
<P>
While campaigning for a "yes" vote in Belfast, the provincial
capital of Northern Ireland, Blair said the splinter groups not
observing the ceasefire must not be allowed to dictate the
political agenda in the province.
</P>
<P>
Referendums on the peace deal are being held in Northern
Ireland and in the neighboring Republic of Ireland on May 22.
</P>
<P>
The political settlement will lead to a new power-sharing
assembly in Belfast and establish a new council to develop links
between Northern Ireland and the Republic.
</P>
<P>
Blair was joined by John Major, the former Conservative prime
minister who had played a key role in initiating the peace process
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In a lunch-time address in Belfast to 300 businessmen, Major
also urged them to back the historic peace agreement reached last
month.
</P>
<P>
"A narrow majority or a big 'yes' from one side and not the
other would present a problem," he said. "It could happen. Let's
hope we get a substantial 'yes' vote."
</P>
<P>
Major predicted a "wall of investment" from abroad if Northern
Ireland voted in favour of the agreement, leading to more jobs and
greater prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,200 people have died in 30 years of sectarian conflict
involving thousands of British troops, republican guerrillas
seeking a united Ireland and pro-British "loyalist" extremists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
