<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Court Finds Former PM's Husband Guilty of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish criminal court on
Wednesday found former Prime Minister Tansu Ciller's husband Ozer
Ciller guilty of misleading a parliamentary commission
investigating the couples' wealth.
</P>
<P>
The court convicted and sentenced him to five months in
prison, but commuted the prison term to a small fine of about 10
U.S. dollars, suspended for five years, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ozer Ciller was found to have presented a parliamentary
commission with false translations of documents pertaining to the
Cillers' ownership of property in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Tansu Ciller became Turkey's first woman prime minister in
1993 and served for nearly three years before entering into a
coalition with arch-rival and current Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz. The Ciller-Yilmaz government collapsed under graft charges
brought by the Islamist opposition. Tansu Ciller was accused of
amassing vast wealth and property while in power.
</P>
<P>
Tansu Ciller then shocked observers by joining a coalition
with the Islamists who helped her vote down the corruption
charges in parliament before the alliance collapsed last June.
</P>
<P>
Parliament voted last month to set up another inquiry into
the Cillers' wealth. Tansu Ciller denied any wrongdoing and has
brought similar charges against Yilmaz, which the parliament also
voted to investigate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
