<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Continue Commitment to Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government will continue its
commitment to helping Jordan develop its national economy through
wide-ranging means, a U.S. official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been helping the kingdom implement economic
reform programs, develop industrial zones and finance small-scale
projects, said Lewis Lak, director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development (USAID)'s mission in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has enlisted much advice from the U.S. in implementing
its economic reform programs, which were started in 1989 to lift
its economy out of predicament starting before the 1990-91 Gulf
crisis, said Lak at a joint press conference with a visiting USAID
delegation.
</P>
<P>
While referring to the small-scale projects, Lak said that
among them are those aimed to improve the quality of water used in
the agricultural sector. Some of Jordan's agricultural products
have been rejected by the regional market for alleged pollution of
irrigation water.
</P>
<P>
Visiting USAID administrator J. Brian Atwood complemented Lak's
remarks by saying that there are also some joint projects such as
pharmaceutic companies that will be hopefully established soon.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the U.S. is studying the possibility of ironing
out the obstacles that prevent foreign investment from flowing
into Jordan, added Atwood, who arrived here Tuesday on a working
visit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ambassador to Jordan Wesley Egan also said that as part of
the U.S. efforts in this regard, officials of the two sides have
been holding talks on issues of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Through these talks, the U.S. intends to support and help the
kingdom implementing the Intellectual Property Law, the
ambassador added. Jordan has been listed by the U.S. as one of the
top countries that violate the law seriously.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from the U.S. Embassy in Jordan,
the U.S. provided the kingdom with a total of 1.55 billion
U.S. dollars of economic and military aid from 1990 to 1997. It is
the second largest donor to the kingdom, coming only after Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
