<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Illegal Arms Shipment to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The report by some Western agencies
about the alleged illegal arms shipment to Sierra Leone which
involved Nigeria was out of fact, a Nigerian defense official
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Britain has begun investigations to
reveal whether Nigeria was involved in illegal shipment of arms
used by the west African peace keeping force (ECOMOG) to restore
the civilian government in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The British report charged that the arms sale was a breach of
the international arms sanctions imposed on Sierra Leone
following the ousting of the legitimate government in a coup last
May.
</P>
<P>
The report said the then ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
of Sierra Leone made the clandestine arms deal with a British
company.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing in the report," and "We never heard of the
deal," Col. Godwin Ugbo, spokesman of the Nigerian Defense
Headquarters, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG was in Sierra Leone to carry out a
peace keeping mission, and arms and ammunition were certainly
needed for such a mission, said Col. Ugbo, adding, "it is
different."
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG drove the military junta out of the capital Freetown
and is mopping up the remnants of the junta forces and allied
rebels, he said, adding that some people who were talking of the
issue were something of hypocrisy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
