<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Earmarks $100m for S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has earmarked 100
million U.S. Dollars in emergency support for Sierra Leone
following the reinstatement of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in
March, a report reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted state radio as saying that a World Bank
delegation was in Sierra Leonean capital Freetown "to assess the
security situation in the country following the suspension of the
bank's programs following the May 25 coup last year".
</P>
<P>
The military junta that seized power in May 1997 was
overthrown by the West African peace-keeping force ECOMOG in
February, though fighting continues in the diamond-rich east of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that the World Bank loan would be used for
"capacity building, for the creation of job opportunities and for
the improvement of the standards of the judiciary in the
country".
</P>
<P>
Senior Finance Ministry officials confirmed that a World Bank
team was in Freetown, adding that this was the first visit since
the bank closed its office in the aftermath of the coup.
</P>
<P>
The officials said delegations from the European Union and
former colonial power Britain were also in Freetown and were
considering emergency help.
</P>
<P>
Though no figures had been decided, sources at the Finance
Ministry said help from these sources "certainly will be around
the figure of the 680 million Dollars the international community
pledged Sierra Leone to rebuild the country after the signing of
the Abidjan peace accord in 1996."
</P>
<P>
The Abidjan accord ended Sierra Leone's five-year-old civil
war and paved the way for the elections that produced the Kabbah
government. But the rebels again took up arms after the May 25
coup and allied with the military junta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
