<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Union Denies Power Cut Threats to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Congress of South African
Trade Unions (COSATU) distanced itself Wednesday from a threat to
cut electricity supplies from South Africa to Swaziland to force
political change in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Vice-president of the South African trade unions coordinating
council, George Nkadimeng, reportedly said on May 1 that COSATU
would cut power supplies from South Africa's state-owned power
utility, Eskom, to Swaziland, unless the Swazi government lifts
the ban on political parties in the coming election.
</P>
<P>
Nkadimeng has reportedly threatened a month-long power cut to
disrupt Swaziland's October elections, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
COSATU public relations officer Nowetu Mpati told Swazi media
that Nkadimeng had no mandate to speak on behalf of COSATU.
</P>
<P>
She said COSATU also distanced itself from the request made by
Nkadimeng that the Swazi government stop writing letters to
President Nelson Mandela complaining about COSATU's joint goods
blockade on Swazi borders with the Swaziland Federation of Trade
Unions (SFTU).
</P>
<P>
Mpati said though COSATU supports the SFTU's boycott call,
Nkadimeng had no right or mandate to speak on COSATU's behalf.
</P>
<P>
She said COSATU had no intention of cutting power supplies to
Swaziland as this would violate a government-to-government
agreement.
</P>
<P>
COSATU would continue to support the SFTU but would do so
through peaceful means and would do nothing to undermine
Swaziland's monarchy, Mpati said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the South African government apologized to the Swazi
government for the union threats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
