<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls on Greece to Take up Issue of PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy
Spokesman Sermet Atacanli on Wednesday called on Greece to take up
the issue of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has
opened a bureau in Athens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Atacanli said that Turkey
is concerned about the opening of the PKK office in Athens.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Turkish Foreign Ministry summoned Greek
ambassador in Ankara Dimitris Nezeretis and gave him a verbal note
in protest against Greece's support for the opening of the PKK
bureau in Athens.
</P>
<P>
The PKK officially opened the bureau in Athens last
Thursday, the first of its kind in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly accused Greece of sheltering and
training PKK rebels. But Greece has denied the charges, saying that
"there is not PKK bureau in Athens."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old separatist war
in eastern and southeastern Turkey for autonomy, which has
claimed about 35,000 lives since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
