<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Final Decision Made on Carriers Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Wednesday that he had not made any final decision about reduction
of U.S. aircraft carriers from two to one in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
"No final decision has been made on that yet," Clinton told
reporters at a joint news conference with Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, defense officials said earlier in the day
that the aircraft carrier Independence was scheduled to leave the
Gulf region in late May and will not be replace at least
temporarily as originally planned by the Norfolk-based carrier
Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
They said the Eisenhower would remain in the naval port
Norfolk, Virginia, until June 10, and the carrier John Stennis
would be in the Gulf alone for about three weeks, maintaining the
watch over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
There would be a "gap, a temporary gap" in the Gulf, a military
source said. "It means there will be one carrier in the Gulf for a
short time," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton called the reports about the timetable
"speculation."
</P>
<P>
"The Eisenhower is sailing on schedule as you probably know,
and there has been some speculation about the timetable there,"
the president said. "I can tell you that (Defense) Secretary
(William) Cohen has not recommended a final decision to me on this
and I have certainly not made one."
</P>
<P>
Last week, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters that the
president was considering cutting back on the dozens of warships
in the Gulf as "the conditions are somewhat less threatening than
when they were being built up."
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said the United States was still keeping "all of
our options open" with regard to tensions with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing I want to reaffirm is our determination to see
the United Nations resolutions complied with and the inspection
regime continue until it finishes its work," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is under mounting pressure from
Capitol Hill to slim the deployment, which lawmakers argue has
proven costly both financially and in troop morale.
</P>
<P>
A seven-senator delegation just back from a tour of overseas
outposts Wednesday said they found the troop morale was extremely
low among U.S. forces sent to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
