<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Aid to Africa in Drug Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Drug
Control Program (UNDCP) has called for more assistance to Africa
in personnel training, employment diversification and judicial
reform to resolve its increasing drug trafficking problem.
</P>
<P>
Releasing its study findings to the press here on Wednesday,
the UNDCP said various African countries are being used as
springboards for international trafficking syndicates from Latin
America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
With 321,292 kilograms of cannabis seized in 1996, Africa
accounted for 12 percent of worldwide cannabis seizures, although
its seizures in cocaine and heroin were negligible, the UNDCP
said.
</P>
<P>
Citing Africa's success in fighting drug trafficking, the UNDCP
said Nigeria has taken a major crackdown with the number of
arrests tripled from 775 in 1995 to 2322 in 1997, of which 2143
were related to cannabis crimes.
</P>
<P>
UNDCP's anti-drug campaign follows the announcement of the U.N.
Special Session on Drugs to be held here on June 8-10 which will
enforce worldwide efforts against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
One of the UNDCP's objectives is to decrease world drug
consumption and supply significantly in ten years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
