<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Dismisses Israel's Criticism on Peace Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Wednesday
dismissed as nonsensical Israel's criticism that the United States
was trying to dictate terms for the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe Israel or any other country should accept the
dictates of the United States in a peace process," Clinton said at
a joint news conference with Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
"We cannot and we should not attempt to impose a peace on parties,
because they have to live with the consequences."
</P>
<P>
Clinton has invited Israeli and Palestinian leaders to
Washington next Monday for a final peace accord if Israel first
accepts U.S. proposals on 13.1 percent withdrawal from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has complained to
Israel's Army Radio that he was ready to go to Washington but did
not want to be pressured into agreeing to "certain conditions that
are unacceptable to us."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was Netanyahu's original idea to try to push
for more rapid momentum toward a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"There's no way in the world I could impose an agreement on
them or dictate... to them even if I wished to do that, which I
don't because when the agreement's over, whether it's in the
Middle East or Ireland or Bosnia or any place else, they have to
live with the consequences," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
