<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Politicians Hails Daimler-Chrysler Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- German politicians Thursday hailed the
proposed merger of Germany's Daimler-Benz AG and the U.S. carmaker
Chrysler as proof of the vigor of German industry and a chance to
create new jobs.
</P>
<P>
German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt described the plan
announced by the two companies earlier Thursday as a "wise step"
and a "extremely important deal" through which the German
industrial giant would be able to secure its presence in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of the German-Franco summit in
Avignon, France, Rexrodt also told the German news agency DPA that
he hoped the merger would help create new jobs in Germany.
</P>
<P>
German Transport Minister Mathias Wissmann said that he saw in
the lastest development a clear opportunity for German industry to
improve its competitive edge and to get a foothold in new markets.
</P>
<P>
Germany's main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) also
saw the marriage of the largest German industrial concern and the
third-largest U.S. carmaker as a further proof of German
industry's strength following media giant Bertelsmann's takeover
of the U.S. publisher Random House and BMW's successful bid for
the British firm Rolls-Royce just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The Daimler-Chrysler merger, which is believed to be the
biggest industrial fusion of all time, would create the world
third-largest carmaker with combined worldwide sales of 130
billion dollars and a combined workforce of 421,000 employees
worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
