<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Cut Oil Excise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government plans to cut
oil excise by an average 18 percent to deal with a sharp decrease
in oil and petroleum product prices on the world market, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In draft legislation published by the government Thursday, the
average rate of excise on oil, including stable gas condensate,
will be lowered from 55 rubles (nine U.S. dollars) to 45 rubles (7.5
dollars) per ton throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
The draft will be submitted to the State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, for review.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1998, oil excises in Russia decreased
by 25 percent, while petroleum product excises fell 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the federal budget lost about 5.6 billion rubles
(916 million dollars) as a result of the sluggish oil market,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Finance Minister Mikhail Motorin said the proposed
measure will cost the budget about 2.6 billion rubles (430 million
dollars) this year, prompting a search for resources to compensate
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said that the decision
was difficult, especially for the budget, but it was inevitable
given the crisis on the international oil market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
