<HEADLINE> Russian Bank Chief Warns of Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Central Bank President Sergei
Dubinin on Thursday warned the government that it was on the edge
of a financial crisis caused by a burgeoning foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted the bank chief as saying that
the consequences of such a crisis would be comparable with the
hyperinflation in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet session devoted to the budget policy through to the
year 2001, Dubinin said in a report that the spending on servicing
of foreign debt in 2001 will exceed 12 percent of total budget
spending.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry had noted the expenditure under the
federal budget for servicing the national foreign debt had risen
from 0.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1993 to 6.85 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Dubinin said the Finance Ministry planned to draw on fewer
external sources for financing the deficit of the federal budget
and use them mostly on a medium-term basis for repaying Russia's
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Dubinin urged the cabinet to step up efforts on tax collection
and to draft budget expenditure on a basis of pessimistic
scenarios. 
</P>
</TEXT>
