<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler, Chrysler Agree on Mega-Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- In a massive shake-up of the global auto
industry, Germany's largest industrial concern Daimler-Benz AG and
Chrysler, the third-largest carmaker in the U.S., announced Thursday
that they will merge into a trans-Atlantic manufacturing giant.
</P>
<P>
The merger, believed to be the biggest industrial fusion of all
time, would create the world's third-largest vehicle firm with
combined worldwide sales of 130 billion U.S. dollars and a
workforce of 421,000.
</P>
<P>
The new company, to be launched by the end of this year under
the name DaimlerChrysler, will have two operational headquarters
in Stuttgart, Germany, and Auburn Hills, Michigan.
</P>
<P>
It will be co-headed by Daimler chief Juergen Schrempp and his
Chrysler counterpart, Robert Eaton.
</P>
<P>
The German newspaper Stuttgarter Zeitung reported, however,
that the Schrempp-Eaton co-management is expected to last three
years, after which Eaton will switch to the supervisory board and
Schrempp will assume sole management.
</P>
<P>
The merger will take the form of a share swap, with Daimler
shareholders acquiring 57 percent of the new company and
Chrysler's 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
With a market capitalization of 92 billion U.S. dollars,
DaimlerChrysler would have "outstanding" prospects for growth
along with new job opportunities, the companies said, adding that
there were no plans for lay-offs or plant closures.
</P>
<P>
With the merger, which still needs to be approved by the
shareholders of both companies and anti-trust authorities, Daimler
and Chrysler said they expected to achieve savings of 1.4 billion
dollars in 1999 and a further three billion dollars annually
within three to five years.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts noted that Chrysler's alliance with
Daimler-Benz would lend it the prestige associated with the German
carmaker and help its efforts to improve car quality.
</P>
<P>
Daimler was also expected to share in the success of Chrysler's
Jeeps and its best-selling minivans, and together, the two
companies would cut costs with a joint strategy for supply and
production.
</P>
<P>
They also said that in an industry plagued by overcapacity, the
Daimler-Chrysler move was most likely to trigger off a wave of
big mergers among rivals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Arrives in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
arrived in Bujumbura, capital of Burundi Thursday afternoon to
have meetings with President Pierre Buyoya and some of the main
politial leaders of the country.
</P>
<P>
Annan's scheduled five-hour stay in Bujumbura for meetings
with army-backed President Pierre Buyoya and some of the main
political leaders, set the stage for his next visit to
neighboring Rwanda, said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to Burundi's National Assembly, Annan, the most
important dignitary to visit Burundi since the army coup in 1996
which installed Major Buyoya, detailed the cost of the country's
protracted ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The profound crisis in Burundi for the past five years has
divided its children, dismantled its institutions, destroyed its
infrastructure, ruined its economy and, in short, put its future
in jeopardy," he said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died due
to the fighting between the Tutsi-dominated army
and rebels of the Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
He told the Burundians that the United Nations stands ready
to help but they have to decide themselves to build a better
future.
</P>
<P>
Annan's aides said his main goal is to promote internal
political negotiations which are still in their infancy.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's visit produced immediate fruits. An aide to
Julius Nyerere, the international mediator on Burundi, announced
on Thursday that the next round of external talks between the
warring parties will be held around June 15 in Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya has met some of the conditions set by regional states
before they will formally lift ineffectual economic sanctions
imposed after the coup.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Annan is due to meet two prominent Hutu
politicians recently released from house detention,including
Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, who was toppled as president in the 1996
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
