<HEADLINE> Orchid Show Held in Honor of Patriotic Chinese General (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-seven years after bidding
farewell to his home in this capital of northeast China's Liaoning
Province, General Zhang Xueliang can only convey his nostalgia
through 13 pots of rare orchids he asked a friend to bring back
here today.
</P>
<P>
The orchids, grown by the general who now lives in Hawaii after
decades of house arrest under Taiwan's Kuomintang regime, were put
on display at his former residence to mark his 98th birthday,
which falls June 3.
</P>
<P>
Also on show are photographs of the general, and paintings and
seal cuttings by leading artists such as the late painter Guo
Xihe, which are birthday presents for Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The display has attracted orchid lovers and admirers of the
general from Beijing, Taiwan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
An almost-legendary figure in modern China, General Zhang,
along with another Kuomintang general called Yang Hucheng,
arrested Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek on December 12, 1936 in
Xi'an, northwest China, and demanded that he cease the civil war
and fight the Japanese invaders in alliance with the Communists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orchid Show Held in Honor of Chinese General (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Xi'an Incident, as it is recorded in history books, led to
the second period of cooperation between the Communist Party of
China (CPC) and the Kuomintang (KMT), the two rival political
factions in the country at the time, which later led to the
Chinese people's victory in the War Against Japanese Aggression
(1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
As a result of defying Generalissimo Chiang, General Zhang
Xueliang was placed under house arrest, first in
mainland China, and then on Taiwan after 1949. He only regained
his freedom in the early 1990s, and went to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
During all those years, General Zhang devoted himself to
growing orchids, said Huang Xiuqiu, the general's friend, who
brought the orchids and is head of a worldwide orchid-growers'
organization.
</P>
<P>
"Hearing that a special orchid show would be held in his
hometown to mark his birthday, the general was highly delighted
and grateful. He wishes good health and happiness to everyone,"
said Huang, who met the general in Hawaii in April.
</P>
<P>
For Liu Peizhi, a former vice-minister of agriculture, this
show is a very special occasion, as the general was his
savior. Around the time of the Xi'an Incident, Liu was sent to
Zhang Xueliang and Yang Hucheng's troops as a representative from
the Red Army, and was nearly shot by the generals' subordinates.
</P>
<P>
"It was General Zhang who gave the order that I be freed, which
saved my life," said Liu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
