<HEADLINE> Philippine Voters Urged to Participate in Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Commission on
Election (Comelec) Thursday urged the country's more than 34
million registered voters to take an active part in the May 11
national and local elections.
</P>
<P>
"I encourage all qualified registered voters to go out, vote
and participate in this democratic process," said Bernardo Pardo,
chairman of the Comelec, the government agency overseeing the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Pardo said that the poll body had made all the necessary
preparations for "clean, honest, orderly, peaceful and credible
elections."
</P>
<P>
The 90-day election campaign period will end Saturday, and a
total of 34,163,465 registered voters are expected to troop to
174,374 precincts next Monday to exercise their sacred right of
suffrage.
</P>
<P>
They will elect a new president as well as a new vice
president, 12 out of 24 senators, all 256 members of the House of
Representatives, 79 provincial governors and 1,608 mayors.
</P>
<P>
The casting of votes will start at seven o'clock in the morning
and end at three o'clock in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to Pardo, candidates, political parties, media and
the general public are allowed to poll watch and have free access
to the results of elections to discourage any attempt to falsify
or tamper with them. 
</P>
