<HEADLINE> U.S. Computer Industry Trade Mission Leader on HK Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- John E. McPhee, leader of a
computer industry trade mission from the United States, said here
Thursday that no one visiting Hong Kong can go away without being
impressed with the vibrant nature of the area and the people.
</P>
<P>
McPhee, acting deputy assistant secretary of Technology and
Aerospace Industries under the U.S. Department of Commerce, said
Hong Kong has an energy about it that is tempered by pragmatism
and the experience that comes from being an Asian business center.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks in an interview with Xinhua before he and
his delegation left here for Shenzhen Thursday afternoon after
attending the opening ceremony of the Computer Expo at the Hong
Kong Conventional and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
"Our trade mission has come to Hong Kong because we know that
business opportunities exist for companies with the latest
information technologies to manage change and increase
productivity," McPhee said.
</P>
<P>
"We know that Hong Kong has an entrepreneurial spirit and a large
number of small and medium sized businesses."
</P>
<P>
In the U.S. economy, he said small and medium-sized companies
have been the largest source of technical innovations, new
employment and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that Hong Kong's economy will also continue to
benefit from the contributions of its small companies," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-U.S. relations, McPhee said that the U.S. and Chinese
governments have a bilateral group called the Joint Commission on
Commerce and Trade (JCCT) which works cooperatively to foster
business and trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Within the JCCT co-chaired by China's minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation and the U.S. secretary of Commerce,
he said, several sub-groups exist, including one that covers the
information technology industries.
</P>
<P>
The Information Technology Sub-group has cooperated in a number
 of work plans which have included many business facilitation
activities.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said this trade mission is one of the events on the
current 1998 work plan that both governments support.
</P>
<P>
Since its formation in 1994, the sub-group has met five times
to review the progress achieved and plan future events.
</P>
<P>
"We are quite pleased with the success of the cooperative
events which the sub-group has sponsored and look forward to
continuing our joint efforts in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
McPhee has been responsible in the Department of Commerce for
analyses, trade policy development and export assistance affecting
the high technology industries for over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that only the private sector has the resources to
develop technical solutions and create the infrastructure that
will be necessary for users globally to conduct business
electronically with the same confidence they do face-to-face or
via telephone," he said.
</P>
<P>
The tremendous growth in the use of the Internet is reflected
in the statistic that usage of the Internet doubles every 100
days, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, one billion people will be using the
Internet, up from 100 million today.
</P>
<P>
"That makes for a very unpredictable, but very exciting
future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
