<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholar: Chinese to Win Nobel Literature Prize in 50 Years (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A famous Chinese scholar said here
today that a Chinese writer would win the country its first Nobel
literature prize in middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Ning of the Beijing Languages and Culture
University said that Chinese literature has made rapid progress in
the past two decades, and has entered a period of preparation for
wining the Nobel Prize. He predicted that if undisturbed by
reasons apart from literature, a Chinese writer would appear in
the Nobel prize-awarding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Wang was the first Ph.D in English comparative literature in
China, and is a member of the International Comparative Literature
Association.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out leading writers Mo Yan, Shi Tiesheng, Wang
Anyi, Yu Hua and Su Tong as possible Nobel winners.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the director of the Association has asked
China's literature professors and critics to recommand Chinese
candidates for the prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholar: Chinese to Win Nobel Literature Prize in 50 Years (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang said that another consideration of the Nobel Committee is
that it also cares about the arrangement of nationalities and
regions. But in its 90 years' history it has never cared much
about China, whose population accounts for one fifth of the
world's total.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the 1919 New Culture Movement, after
division and reconstruction, Chinese literature has merged into
the mainstream of the 20th century's world literature. Early in
the 1930-1940 period, the Nobel Committee noticed great
achievements in Chinese literature, and thought of Lu Xun, Wen
Yiduo and Ai Qing as prize candidates.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted, "For various reasons outside literature, Chinese
didn't realize its wish to win the Nobel Literature prize." He
believed that with economic and culture development, China has
more possibilities now to hold an equal dialogue with the
world. He hoped that foreigners would look at Chinese writers and
literary works without any bias.
</P>
<P>
Another point which should be noted was that while Chinese
literature translators took great effort to introduce foreign
literature works into China, they ignored a more important
task: introducing good Chinese works to the outside. This was an
important reason why Chinese writers were not taken seriously by
the committee.
</P>
<P>
Professor Ma Yueran, chairman of the committee, also noted
this: "Good Chinese literature works do not have fairly good
translation."
</P>
<P>
On the Chinese contemporary literature itself, Wang thought
there had some points worthy of consideration. He said that among
the current Chinese writers, there are few language masters with
profound Chinese and western culture background and aesthetic
cultivation. It will cost 50 years' time to change such situation
utterly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
