<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets Papua New Guinea Parliament Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of China's
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, met with a
delegation of the National Parliament of Papua New Guinea, led by
its speaker, John Pundari, here today.
</P>
<P>
Li said that he hoped that the visit by Pundari and his
entourage would play a positive role in enhancing the friendship
and cooperation between the two nations and their parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China and Papua New Guinea, both in the
Asia-Pacific region, have much in common in international affairs,
despite their geographic distance from each other.
</P>
<P>
It will benefit the peace, stability and development of the two
sides as well as that of the Asia-Pacific region, to strengthen
their friendship and cooperative ties in all areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pundari said China's social and economic development has left
a very deep impression on him.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China had provided aid to Papua New Guinea. From a
long-term point of view, he noted, the bilateral cooperation will
only have vitality if the two nations use their respective
advantages to continue cooperation in new forms.
</P>
<P>
Pundari agreed with him, and said Papua New Guinea is rich in
resources, and welcomes Chinese businesses to invest there. The
two sides can cooperate in the fields of agriculture, fisheries
and mining, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Li thanked the Papua New Guinea government for adhering to
its "one China" policy on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He briefed the visitors on New China's development process
since its founding in 1949, especially the great changes that have
taken place since China initialed reform and opening-up 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
China will encounter many difficulties and problems on the road
ahead, despite the great development already achieved, he added,
but China is confident that it can handle its own matters well,
and ``we have a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
Pundari said both nations have always respected each other's
sovereignty, and Papua New Guinea will, as always, stick to its "one
China" stand.
</P>
<P>
The delegation has toured cities and the countryside in China,
and was deeply impressed by the harmonious lives Chinese people
are leading, and the various rights they enjoy, he noted, adding
that the Chinese government has made great efforts to ensure the
basic rights of its people. 
</P>
