<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Minute Election Registration for Cambodian Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Funcinpec, one of Cambodia's two
ruling parties, scraped in before the deadline Thursday for
registering to compete in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
Parties or individuals who failed to register with the National
Election Committee (NEC) by 17:30 local time Thursday would be
barred from running in the July 26 elections, but those registered
were still subject to approval by the NEC, said NEC officials.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Funcinpec, led by deposed first prime minister
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, 38 other parties including Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and Sam Rainsy
Party, an ally of Funcinpec, were registered.
</P>
<P>
The NEC registration, which began March 28, is the last of two
registrations required to compete in the elections. The first is
with the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec has nominated 122 formal parliamentary candidates
and 130 alternates to compete in 23 cities and provinces.
Prince Ranariddh will stand in the Phnom Penh election district.
</P>
<P>
The CPP, another ruling party and the biggest rival of
Funcinpec, has submitted a list of 122 formal candidates and 140
alternates. Hun Sen will contest the Kompong Cham election
district.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec narrowly won the 1993 election with 58 seats in the
120-seat parliament, but it was forced into a coalition with the
CPP, which won 51 seats, when the CPP threatened to continue the
long-running civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
