<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Says "Not Now" to Talks over Kurils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia has ruled out talks with Japan
on the sovereignty of the disputed South Kuril islands until it is
in a stronger position to negotiate, President Boris Yeltsin's
press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Mayak radio station, the presidential
spokesman said Russia was in a weak state and had no ability to
discuss and resolve "territorial issues".
</P>
<P>
Russia and Japan have been at odds over rival claims to four
islands seized by the Soviet Union after the Second World
War. Many discussions on the issue had been conducted in the last
few years without any substantial results in sight.
</P>
<P>
"Only a strong state can raise and resolve such matters,"
Yastrzhembsky said. "If that is not the case, it is enough to show
weakness just once and a domino effect will follow."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman emphasized a statement he made earlier during a
visit to the South Kurils, the disputed islands, that "Russia does
not have land to spare".
</P>
<P>
On a Russia-Japan treaty to formally end the war, Yastrzhembsky
said all Russian diplomats would proceed from the principle of
Russia's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
A bilateral subcommission charged with formulating a treaty
failed to achieve a breakthrough during its second meeting of
deputy foreign ministers in Moscow Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan has refused to sign a formal treaty with Russia until the
four islands seized by the former Soviet Union are returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
