<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Remove China from Watch List Under "301" Statute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao called on the U.S. government to comprehensively evaluate
China's achievements in protecting intellectual property rights
and to remove China from the watch list under the "Special 301"
statute as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark when responding to a question at today's
news conference.
</P>
<P>
The "Special 301" statute requires the U.S. trade
representatives to review annually the conditions of intellectual
property protection among the U.S. trading partners.
</P>
<P>
After expressing the regrets of the Chinese government for
being listed under the "Special 301" statute, he pointed out that
China has seriously undertaken the obligations in the
Sino-U.S.Intellectual Property Rights Agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has taken comprehensive and powerful
measures to implement the law on protection of intellectual
property rights and launched massive campaigns against piracy.
</P>
<P>
China will, as it always does, promote the protection of
intellectual property rights from legislative, judicial and
administrative aspects, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Cities Urged to Introduce Anti-Disaster Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China should set up comprehensive
systems in its major cities to fight natural calamities and
increase urban areas' ability to prevent disasters.
</P>
<P>
Natural disasters will bring 200 billion to 250 billion yuan
(about 30 billion US dollars) annual economic losses for China in
the coming few years, according to experts attending a symposium
on reducing disasters here today.
</P>
<P>
Specialists in urban construction and disaster prevention
suggest that China should establish comprehensive urban disaster
prevention systems by means of engineering technology,
legislation, administration and education to guarantee the
sustainable development of cities.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of China's large cities and half of the
country's population are located in the country's eastern coastal
areas, which are vulnerable to floods, earthquakes, and
meteorological and marine calamities.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of cities act as the windows of China's
opening-up. Their safety is of vital importance to the nation's
economy and the people's livelihood," said Chen Weibang from the
China Urban Science Institute.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 50 percent of China's national income and
70 percent of its gross value of industrial output are produced in
the urban areas. At present, the country's urban population
accounts for about 30 percent of the total, and the ratio
will increase to 45 percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that natural disasters in cities are more complex
than in the countryside. For instance, earthquakes may cause
fires, cut off water supplies and cause outbreaks of
pestilence. "Programs to prevent earthquakes, floods and fires
should be included in the comprehensive plans for urban
development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that related departments should formulate laws and
regulations to define the responsibilities of governments and
enterprises in the work of disaster prevention and alleviation. In
addition, more input is needed in research into anti-seismic and
anti-fire technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Foreign Exchange Reserve Hits 35 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign exchange reserve
reached 35.54 billion U.S. dollars by the end of April 1998, up
15.5 percent from the previous month, the central Bank of Korea
(BOK) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The mounting foreign exchange reserve, excluding South Korean
banks' foreign currency holdings at their overseas branches, hit
30 billion U.S. dollars two months earlier than the end-of-June
deadline set by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Last December, South Korea signed an agreement with the IMF for
a bailout loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars tied with tough
conditions.
</P>
<P>
It was also the first time that the country surpassed the mark
in nearly two years since July 1996, when saw the reserve stood at
31.24 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bankers attributed the rising reserve to the nation's
continuing current account surplus, insurance of bonds valued at
3.29 billion U.S. dollars in the United States last month and
improvement of liquidity among domestic financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world, has
been in a financial crisis caused by corporate bankruptcies and
bad loans of financial institutions since late 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Trade with Mainland for Outward Processing Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's total
exports to the Chinese mainland for outward processing last year
rose by 10 percent to 244.9 billion HK dollars (31.39 billion U.S.
dollars) over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released by the Census and Statistics
Department Thursday show that the value of Hong Kong's
domestic exports to the Chinese mainland for outward processing
amounted to 47.1 billion HK dollars (6.04 billion U.S. dollars), a
nine percent increase over 1996 while that of re-exports to the
mainland for outward processing was estimated to be 197.8 billion
HK dollars (25.35 billion U.S. dollars), representing an increase
of 10 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period of comparison, the value of imports from
the Chinese mainland related to outward processing registered an
increase of eight percent to 491.1 billion HK dollars (62.96
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, 595.5 billion HK dollars (76.34 billion U.S.
dollars) of Hong Kong's re-exports of the Chinese mainland origin
to other places were produced through outward processing in the
mainland, representing an increase of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Information on trade involving outward processing in the
mainland is collected in a sample survey conducted by the Census
and Statistics Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
