<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Denies Plans to Recruit School Leavers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A government spokesman Thursday
denied plans to launch a new recruitment drive targeting school
leavers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, government spokesman and
Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera said the government has no
plans whatsoever to recruit school children to the army as
reported by the weekend Sunday Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The minister accused the newspaper of deliberately carrying the
report saying that the army was targeting school children to
coincide with a visit to the country by a senior UN official.
</P>
<P>
Special representative of the UN Secretary General Olaara
Otunna arrived in Colombo Sunday on a week-long tour to study the
impact of Sri Lanka's war on children.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times reported that the military was planning to ask
village officials to identify schools where officers could carry
out propaganda campaigns to encourage youngsters to enlist.
</P>
<P>
He said publication of such reports will benefit the rebels.
There is a doubt in the publication of such baseless reports at a
time when the UN envoy is touring Sri Lanka to inquire into
children who are involved in the war.
</P>
<P>
This would create a negative image within the international
community, said the minister. 
</P>
