<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Contacts Continuing Over Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Thursday that contacts are continuing over the
possible Washington talks next Monday, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who made the remarks during a meeting of the
Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, did
not elaborate what kind of contacts he was making.
</P>
<P>
But he indicated that he was in contact with related parties so
that Israel would accept the U.S. invitation to attend the White
House summit, which is due to launch the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
After her separate meetings with Israeli and Palestinian
leaders in London early this week, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright stressed that the American invitation is
conditional.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Israel must accept the U.S. peace proposal
before the summit, which calls on Israel to hand over 13.1 percent
of the West Bank to the Palestinians during the second
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israel has insisted that any redeployment of more than 9
percent would damage its national security interests. And the
right-wing parties have threatened to topple the government if
Netanyahu agrees to a 13 percent withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu may ask the U.S. to
delay the Washington talks for a few days to give him more
time to discuss the American plan with the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Channel Two of Israel Television
Wednesday night, Netanyahu publicly called for U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross to return to the region before Monday to modify
the American initiative.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reiterated that he would not accept any dictates
from anyone.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that the Israeli stand on redeployment
was acceptable both to the Israeli public and the U.S. congress.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a letter, signed by 220 members of the
House of Representatives, to U.S. President Bill Clinton, which
urged him to avoid public pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak Thursday
called on Netanyahu not to argue about the percentage points so as
to find a way to complete the arrangements for the pullback.
</P>
<P>
Knesset member Yossi Beilin also said that Israel is in the
danger of losing the American support, terming the U.S. backing as
Israel's second most important security asset after the Israeli
Defense Forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
