<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Invites Bids for Sewage Treatment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- This east China metropolis today
invited bids for designs for a new sewage treatment project to
be constructed in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
When the new sewage treatment project is completed, all of
Shanghai's waste water will be properly treated by sewage
treatment facilities instead of being directly discharged into
local rivers, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now produces about five million cu m of liquid sewage
daily, most of which used to be discharged into the Suzhou and
Huangpu rivers or their tributaries without any proper treatment
due to a lack of necessary treatment facilities, severely
polluting these rivers.
</P>
<P>
The city spent 2.5 billion yuan building a pipeline facility on
the northern bank of the Suzhou River in the early 1990s. The project,
with a designed capacity of treating 1.7 million tons of sewage
daily, now treats 1.4 million tons of liquid sewage collected
from nearby urban districts and discharges the treated water into
the Yangtze River estuary.
</P>
<P>
Construction started on another pipeline facility last year on
the upper reaches of the Huangpu River, a major source of urban
water supplies. The project, which will cost 4.8 billion yuan,
will have a designed daily treatment capacity of 1.7 million cu
m of sewage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
