<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Opens First Production Base in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Intel's first production base in
China began operation here today when the company's chairman
Dr. Andrew Grove and a Shanghai official cut the ribbon this morning
for a factory in the Pudong Waigaoqiao Bonded Area.
</P>
<P>
As part of Intel Technology (China) Ltd., the factory, which
cost 198 million US dollars to complete, was put into operation four
months ahead of schedule, and specializes in assembling and testing
flash memory.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Intel Technology (China) Ltd. is a
major part of Intel's global strategy. And the factory is Intel's
second of its kind in the world, according to Dr. Grove.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai factory covers an area of 35 acres and employs 400
people.
</P>
<P>
Intel has opened representative offices in 12 major Chinese
cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, and will set up a
research center in Beijing during the second quarter of this
year, Dr. Grove said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
