<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Natural Disasters Pose Threats to China's Economy'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expert predicted today
that natural disasters will cause increasingly bigger losses to
China's economy at the turn of the century, costing a total of 200
billion to 250 billion yuan (about 30 billion US dollars) each
year.
</P>
<P>
The direct economic losses, quadruple the figure for the early
1980s, will be caused mainly by droughts, floods, typhoons and
frost, Prof. Ma Zongjin, an academician with the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, told a national symposium on reducing natural
disasters in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said natural disasters caused an average of 36.2
billion yuan (about 4.3 billion US dollars) in direct economic
losses a year during 1950s, and the figure rose dramatically to
102.1 billion yuan (about 12.3 billion US dollars) by the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Since 1949 more than 500,000 people have died in natural
disasters in China, which cost a total of 2.5 trillion yuan (about
300 billion US dollars) in economic losses, statistics showed, and
the average economic losses amounted to three to six percent of
the country's GDP a year, much higher than in the developed
countries, such as the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Natural disasters have already became a major factor that
hinders economic growth in China," said Zhou Guangzhao,
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress and chairman of the Chinese Association for Science and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the countries which suffers the most seriously
from natural disasters, due to its large population, complicated
climate, geographic conditions and vulnerable ecological
environment, Zhou explained.
</P>
<P>
The key to reducing losses from natural disasters lies in the
prediction and assessment of major disasters, Prof. Ma noted.
</P>
<P>
He called on experts in the social sciences to make joint
efforts together with experts in the natural sciences to reduce
losses from natural disasters, which also affect many other
aspects of society in addition to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium, the third of its kind to be held in
China, is organized by the Chinese Association for Science and
Technology as one of the activities to mark the "International
Decade for Reducing Natural Disasters". It has attracted more than
500 scientists from all over the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
