<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Germany's Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp. will announce
Thursday a 30 billion U.S. dollars merger that would combine the
maker of the Mercedes-Benz with a once-struggling automaker that
returned to prominence with a "Buy American" campaign.
</P>
<P>
-- House members of both parties Wednesday blasted the Clinton
administration for trying to force Israel to accept U.S. terms for
negotiations with the Palestinians, underlining the political
stakes for the president in confronting the Jewish state and its
legions of supporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Peace talks between the Sudanese government and the southern
rebels ended on a note of progress, as both sides agreed to accept
an internationally supervised vote on self-determination for the
southern half of the country.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon announced that Cuba is not that much of a
threat to American national security.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesian unrest spread in response to IMF-backed
austerity measures. At least four cities saw protests over sharp
price rises.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Ministers Benjamin Netanyahu said he may turn
down an invitation for Middle East talks in Washington next week
if it means bowing to U.S. pressure to withdraw from 13 percent of
the West Bank. 
</P>
