<HEADLINE> China Works with UNESCO, Japan to Rebuild Imperial Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China is working with the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO)
and Japan to rebuild part of an imperial palace situated near
Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Following more than three years of concerted preparations
between the three parties, rebuilding work on the basis of the
site of the imperial palace started here today.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony to mark the beginning of the project
were Zhang Pai, deputy director of China's State Cultural Relics
Bureau, Nobaru Noguchi, UNESCO representative in Beijing, and
Yutaka Yoshizawa, a Japanese diplomat stationed in China.
</P>
<P>
The Hanyuan Hall of the imperial palace of the Tang Dynasty
(618-907) was completed in the year 663. The huge
complex was destroyed in a war at the end of the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 UNESCO decided to rebuild the Hanyuan Hall, with Japan
offering one million US dollars to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
From 1995 to 1996 archaeologists with the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences conducted a thorough survey of the site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
