<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Bank Raises Certificate Rates Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI), the central
bank, announced here Thursday to raise BI certificate (SBI)
interest rates by between 4 percent and 12 percent in a bid to
stabilize the rupiah currency against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, BI Governor Syahril Sabirin said the
central bank was forced to make the choice of raising the SBI
rates following recent developments which have disturbed the
government's efforts to stabilize the rupiah, especially the
non-technical factors.
</P>
<P>
The governor, however, did not give details about the
non-technical factors.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, overnight SBI interest rate will
be raised from 44 percent to 48 percent, two-day SBI rate will be
raised from 45 percent to 49 percent and three to six days SBI
rate will be raised to 50 percent from 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate for one-week SBI will be raised from 48
percent to 54 percent while two weeks SBI rate will be raised from
49 percent to 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
The one month SBI rate will be increased to 58 percent from 50
percent, the two months rate will be increased to 48 percent from
44 percent and the three months rate will be raised to 44 percent
from 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
For six months and one year SBI, the rates will be raised
respectively from 23 percent to 34 percent and from 21 percent to
33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SBI is short-term rupiah-denominated obligations issued by
the central bank to drain excess liquidity from the market.
</P>
<P>
This was the third time since March 23 this year for Bank
Indonesia to raise SBI rates following the fluctuation of the
rupiah and the sharp increase of the prices of basic commodities
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the rupiah, which has lost more than 70
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar in the past ten
months, picked up to 7,000/8,000 per dollar from 9,000/10,000 per
dollar in the last few weeks following the signing of economic
reform program between Indonesia and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
However, it dropped to 9,400/10,000 per dollar Thursday.
Analysts said the heated political situation undermined the
positive signal from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations staged by students in the country in the last
two months have spread in recent days and some riots have taken
place in several cities, military authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
