<HEADLINE> Xinhua, Reuters Heads Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The heads of Xinhua and Reuters news
agencies exchanged views here today on expanding exchanges and
cooperation between their two news agencies and the other media of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Guo Chaoren, president of the Xinhua News Agency, meeting Peter
Job, managing director of the Reuters Group, said Xinhua and
Reuters, as two influential news agencies worldwide, share a
long-term relationship of mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
There exist broad prospects for future cooperation between
Xinhua and Reuters, he noted, adding that he looked forward to
more contacts, deeper understanding and wider areas for
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
Guo briefed the visitors on the development of Xinhua, saying
that over the past few decades Xinhua has established branches in
more than 100 countries and set up a global communications
network, which has enabled Xinhua to become a global news agency
by and large.
</P>
<P>
Job said Reuters values its relationship with China, and that
he hopes the two agencies will carry out more fruitful cooperation
in news coverage, photographs and information, which will serve
China's modernization, reform and opening-up endeavors.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Guo on Reuters' development of economic
information, prevention of financial risks and development of
software.
</P>
<P>
Reuters was the first Western news agency to establish a
cooperative relationship with Xinhua when the two signed an
agreement on news exchanges in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Job, here at the invitation of Xinhua, visited Shanghai before
arriving in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
