<HEADLINE> ``China's Shipping Sector Contributes to Economic Growth'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official today said
that China's shipping sector has contributed greatly to the
country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Hong Shanxiang, vice minister of Communications, made the
remark at a six-day seminar which opened today in this east China
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1997 the country had more
than 2,000 berths for ships of 10,000 dwt, which handled 36,000
ships from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the inland river shipping mileage reached 110,000
km, including a 5,800-km route which can handle 1,000-dwt vessels.
</P>
<P>
China's container shipping has maintained a rapid growth rate
of 25 percent in the past decade. The business volume reached ten
million TEUs (20-Foot Equivalent Units) in 1997, up 31 percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China has drawn up an overall plan to promote the development
of the sector in the next few years. By the year 2000 the country
will have built 100 new berths and to have increased its handling
capacity by 200 million tons a year. Conditions on 2,400 km of
inland water routes will also have been improved.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 experts and officials from overseas and China
attended the seminar, named the "International Workshop on
Shipping Policies and Development"
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by China's Ministry of Communications, the seminar is
expected to promote the healthy development of the sector and
improve Sino-overseas cooperation in this respect.
</P>
<P>
The specialists attending will discuss the future of the
shipping industry, China's shipping policy, international
shipping competition and other related topics.
</P>
<P>
A research tour will be held during the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
