<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will inaugurate on May 26 the second
International Fair on Agricultural, Animal Wealth and Food
Production, the Middle East News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day fair will be attended by Egyptian agricultural
companies and foreign companies from Jordan, Bahrain, the Untied
Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Italy, the Czech Republic, Qatar,
Greece, Ireland and Australia.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- More than 100 investment enterprises will be set up in
Egypt's Cairo governorate aimed at providing around 70,000 job
opportunities, the Al-Ahram daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Governor Abdul Reheem Shehata told the Arabic-language daily
that the enterprises will cost 4 billion Egyptian pounds (1.18
billion U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
They will be set up in Qattamiya, Nasr City, Zahraa El-Maadi,
Tura and Helwan, he added
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has planned to establish a free trade zone at
Khor El-Zubeir, Basra province in an effort to accelerate economic
and social development by attracting foreign investments,
introducing up-to-date technology and providing new labor
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A conference on Arab capital markets due to open in
Beirut on Thursday will seek ways of effectively curbing foreign
ownership of Arab stock markets, the Egyptian newspaper the World
Today reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference will help standardize Arab bank regulations and
remove obstruction to free movement of Arab capital, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by a group of economists and
businessmen in cooperation with the Central Bank of Lebanon, the
Lebanon Banks Association and an international financing
agency.
</P>
<P>
It will last for a few days and be attended by 800 specialists
and experts in financial and economic sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
