<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Plunges Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah on Thursday
closed at 8,400/9,400 against the U.S. dollar in the Jakarta money
exchange market, a sharp decrease compared to Wednesday's close of
7,900/8,400 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah broke through the level of 10,000 per dollar in the
morning trading, and gradually recovered at noon, currency dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the heated political situation triggered by
students demonstrations in the country's big cities was the main
cause of the weakness of the local currency.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the approval for the release of the IMF
(International Monetary Fund) bailout fund on May 4 was
overshadowed by students protests, urging the government to cut
skyrocketing prices and introduce major economic and political
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 70 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar since July last year when the monetary crisis hit
the Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, central bank director Miranda S. Goeltom said the
government will not interfere in the market to stabilize the
rupiah. "We can carry out a consistent policy to strengthen the
value of rupiah," the director noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
