<HEADLINE> China's Health Minister Leaves for World Health Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Chinese
government, led by Health Minister Zhang Wenkang, left here today
for Geneva to attend the 51st World Health Assembly May 11-16.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Zhang will address the assembly, commenting on the
achievements of the World Health Organization (WHO) over the past
half century, looking forward to health developments in the next
century, and briefing participants on the principles and policies
of China's health services as well as reform and development in
this area.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Switzerland, Zhang will meet senior
officials from the WHO Secretariat and former Norwegian Prime
Minister G.H. Brundtland, secretary general-elect, and discuss how
to expand cooperation between China and the WHO.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also will sign a memorandum of cooperation with
Britain. Zhang also expects to exchange extensive views with
health ministers of other countries on bilateral cooperation and
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 30 topics on the agenda of the coming
assembly, including deliberating the 1998 World Health Report,
activities marking the 50th anniversary of the establishment of
the WHO, formulating the Health for All Strategy in the 21st
Century and delivering the World Health Declaration, passing the
nomination for the secretary general, and reviewing the WHO
Constitution and regional arrangements.  
</P>
