<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Recovery Not Far, Reforms Needed: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) predicted
Thursday that the recovery of the Asian economy from the financial
crisis will take place in a couple of years though a specific
timetable is not available now.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he called for reforms of economic and
financial systems in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The prediction and call came from the second session of the
on-going Ninth Annual Corporate Conference of the Asia Society,
which was held Thursday at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center.
</P>
<P>
Responding to inquiries from the audience after delivering a
keynote address at the session, HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa said: "If it is a normal situation, I would think it will take
Asia a couple of years to bottom out and then recovery will
start."
</P>
<P>
However, he added that it is really very difficult to tell the
timetable because market forces are at play, events which are very
often beyond the control of any single government at play, and
these are all forces that will affect the speed of recovery.
</P>
<P>
As for the cause of the crisis in Asia, Tung pointed out in his
address that the recent Asian financial crisis is a new phenomenon
brought about by an increasingly open global financial market
system.
</P>
<P>
He said that the existing international and multinational
structure for international trade and finance was designed 50
years ago and that needs to be upgraded to suit the new
environments for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, Hong Kong fully supports calls for global
efforts to design a new international financial architecture,"
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung's idea was shared by Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister Pham
Gia Khiem, who also delivered a keynote address at the session.
</P>
<P>
Pham said that with the support of the world community,
countries and regions in Asia will be able to get their economies
recovered soon in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on Asian countries and regions to abandon
the easy-going way of growth and continue economic reforms and
integration.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the present conditions of the economic crisis
require the governments and people of these countries ... on one
hand fully develop all economic potentials and comparative
advantages in human resources and on the other hand completely
abandon the easy-going way of growth, persistently continue
economic reforms and integration, combine domestic strength with
external assistance," Pham said.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, he added, "we shall be able to gradually get the
situation right and build up an Asia of more dynamic and
sustainable development based on a new foundation more adaptive to
changes as mankind enters the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
President Mitsuo Sato of the Asian Development Bank also
delivered a keynote speech at the session, calling for reforms of
financial institutions on a broad basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
