<HEADLINE> HK to Conduct Telephone Poll for Public Opinions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Home Affairs Bureau of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government will
conduct a five-day survey over residential telephones to gauge
the public's perception of problems in the SAR, it was announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The May 11-15 survey will be the 76th in the series to monitor
public opinion trends over perceived problems in Hong Kong,
government's overall performance and expectations about the local
situation.
</P>
<P>
A resident from each household aged between 15 and 64 will be
contacted in the evening by using a random sample of residential
telephone numbers contained in the latest local telephone
directory.
</P>
<P>
A Home Affairs Bureau spokesman assured that all information
provided by the respondents would be treated with the strictest
confidence and it would not be used for any purpose other than the
survey.
</P>
<P>
"The respondents may wish to know that their assistance will
contribute to a better mutual understanding between the public and
the government. The few minutes it takes for them to respond to
the survey questionnaires would surely serve the greater good of
the community," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
