<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar dived half a
U.S. cent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 63.58 U.S. cents, from 64.10 late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It had begun the day at 63.73 U.S. cents, following a fall in
the price of gold and a weaker Japanese yen against the United
States dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said it was "comfortable for the present with
maintaining the current structure of short-term interest rates."
</P>
<P>
However, it said the stance of policy will be continually
reviewed as new information comes to hand about the likely course
of inflation and activity, including the impact of the Asian
crisis on growth and the strength of domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar received a brief reprieve through the
release of better-than-expected employment figures, but renewed
its downward journey as interest rate speculation overshadowed the
data.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said the number of employed
people in Australia rose 58,200 to 8,572,100 in April, following a
15,500 fall in March.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate was a seasonally adjusted 7.9 percent in
April, from 8.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 84.72 from 84.85 against
Japanese yen, and at 1.1235 from 1.1359 against Deutsche marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
