<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down Marginally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket Thursday
closed down marginally, as the National Australia Bank's (NAB's)
first half profit result met expectations and it raised its
dividend.
</P>
<P>
Funds manager AUSBIL Partners equities director Paul Xiradis
said that the banking sector made modest gains and the NAB's
interim performance after abnormals had been at the upper end of
market expectations.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 7.2 points, or 0.26
percent, at 2780.8, trading between a high of 2788.0 and a low of
2761.0.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index dropped 12.5 points, or 1.05 percent,
to 1179.2, with resources giant BHP continuing to lose ground,
falling 29.2 cents, or 2.01 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both speculation that BHP could appoint an internal replacement
for former chief executive John Prescott and concern that
commodity sales to Japan could be hit by the weak Japanese economy
were weighing on the stock, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed down 2.5 points at 4784.7,
with Westpac Banking Corp, ANZ Banking Group, Lend Lease Corp,
Woolworths, Coles Myer and Rio Tinto halting further declines.
</P>
<P>
Topping turnover was Telstra Corp with 12.71 million shares
traded, valued at 46.72 million Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a thin 262.61 million shares valued at
819.33 million Australian dollars (524.37 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises 658 to 388, with 429 stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 22.5 points, or 1.68 percent, at
1316.1 after gold bullion fell 2.85 to 300.70 U.S. dollars in
Sydney trading. 
</P>
