<HEADLINE> Egypt Stresses Strength of Ties With Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian presidential advisor Osama
al-Baz has said on Thursday that Egypt and Qatar share strong
relations based on sisterly Arab ties, Arab solidarity and unity
of destiny.
</P>
<P>
In an interview over the telephone with the Voice of Arabs
Radio from Doha, al-Baz said his on-going visit to Qatar comes
within the context of bilateral consulations over pressing issues
in the region and the current developments of the peace process in
addition to means of confronting challenges facing the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
He said he conveyed a message to Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Ben
Khalifa Al Thani from President Hosni Mubarak on the Mideast peace
process developments, bilateral ties and issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
He said that he discussed with Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh
Hamad Ben Jassem Ben Jabr Al Thani on the forthcoming meeting of
foreign ministers of the Damascus Declaration group, to be held in
the Qatari capital by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, originally set for early this year, was postponed
due to a growing row between the two countries after Cairo
boycotted the Middle East and North Africa economic conference
hosted by Doha last November. Egypt recalled its ambassador, but
sent him back later.
</P>
<P>
Al-Baz on Tuesday started a three-day visit to Doha, nearly two
months after the Qatari emir held talks with Mubarak in Cairo in
what was viewed as a fence-mending effort to end disputes between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The relations of the two Arab countries soured in 1996 when
Qatar accused Egypt of involvement in a failed coup in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
A summit meeting mediated by Saudi King Fahd between the Qatari
emir and Mubarak at the end of last year failed to bridge the gaps
between the two sides. Qatar later expelled Egyptian laborers.
</P>
<P>
But there seemed to be a thaw in their relations after the two
countries signed an agreement earlier in March to allow Egyptian
workers back to finish their contract terms in Qatar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
