<HEADLINE> Digital Boosts Exposure in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Digital Corp. of the United States
today delivered the first batch of personal computers (PC) to a
local buyer that were produced in its China-based factory.
</P>
<P>
Digital has followed IBM and Hewlett Packard to locate a
production base in China.
</P>
<P>
Franklin Sze, Digital's manager in charge of PC products in the
Asia-Pacific region, said that the establishment of factories in
China will help the company cut costs and provide supply and
service to Chinese users in the quickest way.
</P>
<P>
Digital's branch in China, known as Digital Equipment China
Inc. (DEC), set up a joint venture factory with Start, the largest
producer of computer peripherals in China. The factory is in
Fuzhou, a city in south China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The 30-million-U.S.-dollar joint venture produces Digital
desktop PCs and servers based on PT II and MMX.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Digital said that the Fuzhou factory has a
capacity of producing 300 PCs every day.
</P>
<P>
Chinese manufacturers now have more than 60 percent of China's
PC market.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months international computer manufacturers
have stepped up efforts to localized their business in
China. Intel opened a large computer chip plant in Shanghai today.
</P>
<P>
Intel is a major supplier for China's PC manufacturers,
including the Legend Group which turned out its one millionth PC
on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
