<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan to Persuade Buyoya to Accept Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan said here Thursday that he will
encourage Burundi President Pierre Buyoya to accept the mediation
over the Burundi crisis for a national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a press conference before leaving for the Burundian
capital of Bujumbura in the morning, Annan reaffirmed the UN
support for the efforts by the leaders in the Great Lakes region
to find a way out for the Burundi crisis.
</P>
<P>
"My message to President Buyoya would be to encourage him to
press ahead with the reconciliation and reach out with other
parties and work with (former) President Nyerere and regional
leaders to solve the conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary General noted that some progress has been made
for Burundi to meet certain conditions set by Nyerere and other
regional leaders for lifting the economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks were stalled last year after the
military authority led by President Pierre Buyoya said it had no
faith in Nyerere, the international mediator in the Burundi
political conflicts, who advocates imposing economic sanctions on
the central African nation.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), have imposed sanctions on Burundi since
August of 1996, two months after Major Buyoya toppled a civilian
government led by President Ntibantunganya.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the refugees situation in western Tanzania,
Annan said that the UN will do what it can do to help them. He
also appreciated the Tanzanian government's hospitality to the
refugees especially the new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the numbers (of refugees fleeing into Tanzania)
will not grow", he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan also said that the UN will continue to investigate the
human rights situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo, but
its relationship with Congo is much wider than the human rights.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that on May 17, the head of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) will attend a conference in Congo to
explore the types of assistance the UNDP can provide.
</P>
<P>
"There has been quite a lot of negligence of that country," he
said. "They need assistance in infrastructure repairs,
institution building, the social and economic development for the
establishment of a good governance."
</P>
<P>
Questioned about what UN can help Tanzania, one of the poorest
countries in the world, Annan said he has recommended to the UN
to give consideration to relieve heavy debt burden of African
countries.
</P>
<P>
On the peace progress in the Middle East, the UN chief said
that the UN has played a very constructive role and will work
with all the parties concerned to really work together and make
the kind of compromise necessary to realize a real and lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
"What I hope and plead for is that we make progress on the
Palestinian front and eventually on the Lebanese and Syrian as
well," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Wednesday afternoon from a visit in
the northern region of Arusha, had meetings with Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa and foreign minister Jakaya Kikwete
about the regional issues, Tanzania's role of peace keeping and
the UN-Tanzanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner after the talks at the State House
Wednesday night, President Mkapa expressed appreciation for
Annan's recent report to the UN Security Council which calls for
more attention to and investment in the poorest continent of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is on his first official visit to Tanzania since he
came to office as the UN Secretary General, spoke highly of
Tanzania's role in the liberation of the Southern Africa and in
the world affairs especially in its support to the U.N. affairs
like hosting hundreds of thousands of refugees from the Great
Lakes region countries.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief also said that Africa now is at a turning point
for development as the whole continent witnessed less conflicts
and has made economic progress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Arusha Tuesday, Annan was encouraged by
the progress made by the International Criminal Tribunal for
Rwanda (ICTR), saying that the Tribunal has effected major
improvements in its operations and is moving ahead to fulfil its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks were apparently to clear the air over mounting
criticism on the inefficiency of the ICTR in executing cases.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal opened its first trial only in January last year,
more than two years after its establishment in November, 1994
under a UN Security Council resolution. But only two cases are
approaching its final leg till now.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived from Nairobi, Kenya, toured the ICTR
premises and attended a court session before departing for
sightseeing in the well-known Ngorongoro Crater National Park
with his wife Nane Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
