<HEADLINE> Sudan Govt Calls for Truce Following Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Khartoum negotiators voiced a
strong call for ceasefire Thursday, one day after the end of
their peace talks at which the southern rebels claimed new
advance on the battle fields.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) said Wednesday
that they seized Wadega garrison in Southern Blue Nile State
while the three-day talks went under way.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Sudan is ready to accept an immediate
cease-fire and cession of hostilities if the other party
reciprocates," said Riek Machar, the Assistant of the President
of Sudan at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"The ceasefire... has been called by Khartoum since January...
The IGAD summit also called for ceasefire, the European Union,
less than a week ago, called for ceasefire, and yesterday the
U.N. Security Council also called for ceasefire,"
</P>
<P>
"We wished the SPLA can be responding" to these calls aimed at
ensuring free and safe humanitarian access to the southern Sudan
where famine is biting, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that the Islamic law should remain as the
main source of the country's constitution on which Khartoum is to
hold a national referendum this month. The separation of state
and religion is one of the key goals for which the SPLA has
fought since 1983.
</P>
<P>
However, Machar said there was a certain progress achieved by
the negotiations this time.
</P>
<P>
"We're happy with the results of this second round of peace
talks. For reasons: the agreement on humanitarian access to the
needed population in southern Sudan" and on an internationally
supervised vote on self-determination for the south, he said.
</P>
<P>
Series of peace talks between the Sudanese warring sides
restarted at the end of October last year after a three-year
deadlock due to the brokering of the regional Inter-Government
Authority of Development group.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the just-ended talks, the Sudanese government agreed
to allow U.N. aid agencies to fly five C0130 aircraft and other
modes of transport to deliver food and other humanitarian items
to famine-affected areas in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The war broke out in 1983 between the Moslem-ruled Khartoum
government in the north and the SPLA demanding more autonomy and
religion freedom in the animist and Christian-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 1.3 million Sudaneses have been killed by the
war and war-related famines. Another 365,000 now live on alien
lands as refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
