<HEADLINE> Second-phase Resettlement Project Starts at Three Gorges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The second-phase resettlement work
of the Three Gorges Project, China's largest water conservation
project, has begun, involving nearly 500,000 farmers and workers.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-2003 resettlement project covers 11 districts and
counties of Chongqing Municipality, involving approximately 15
billion yuan of static investment, and is also part of the effort
to put the water project's first generators into operation in 2003.
</P>
<P>
For this year's work, 2.85 billion yuan is planned to resettle
about 67,000 people, and to move or rebuild 181 factories. The
focus will be placed on land development, infrastructure and
housing.
</P>
<P>
Ministries and provinces have opened 575 projects in this
effort, responding to the central government's call to help the
city.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is also making greater efforts to make the most of
the assistance and resettlement to develop highly efficient
eco-agriculture and restructure its industrial economy.  
</P>
