<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Should Set Up Special Tribunals for Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi President Shahabuddin
Ahmed has suggested that special tribunals be set up for quick
disposal of serious default bank loan cases in the country, media
reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president made this suggestion while inaugurating a lecture
on banking ethics in Dhaka Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Till today, the amount of money due from the defaulters is
about 140 billion taka (about 3.04 billion U.S. dollars), and its
non-payment had been disrupting the banking system," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recently publication of a list of 2,117 loan
defaulters having loans of over 10 million taka (about 2.2 million
dollars), he said "it is undisputed that the big borrowers are the
worst defaulters, and it is they who pose threat to the national
economy."
</P>
<P>
For this, he pointed out, the genuine businessmen and
industrialists were being deprived of bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector "will be strangled unless the government
enables the bank authorities to take action against the
influential and manipulative loan defaulters and their
collaborators," he stressed. 
</P>
