<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Blamed for Increase in Cardiovascular Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Dietary changes have raised the
incidence of cardiovascular diseases fivefold in Shijiazhuang
City, capital of north China's Hebei Province, in the past 20
years.
</P>
<P>
A 20-year follow-up investigation by the Hebei Academy of
Medical Science shows that the death toll from cardiovascular and
cerebrovascular disease has accounted for at least 30 percent of
the disease death toll in Hebei Province in the past dozen years.
</P>
<P>
The investigation focused on the nutrition elements in urban
and rural residents' diets found that with an improved living
standard the amount of grain in people's calorie intake dropped
from 65 percent to 17 percent while their daily intake of
cholesterol reached 691 milligrams, double the level recommended
by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the investigation indicated that Hebei
residents' daily diet contains too much fat, protein and edible
oil which contribute to the development of cardiovascular
diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
