<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Senior Nigerian officials have
accused Western nations of funding the May Day riot in the
southwestern city of Ibadan, which had led to at least seven
deaths.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon attended by diplomats in Abuja
Wednesday, Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said the Nigerian
government had found out that the Ibadan protests were funded by
some foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is indeed known that those who perpetrated the act in
Ibadan were funded and financed by some Western countries which
have made it their own commitment that except one or two of their
friends take power in Nigeria, they will not have the legitimate
choice of Nigerians," said Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
The minister said further that there were some Western
European countries "that have made it a point to ensure that they
support crisis, terrorism and destruction in Nigeria".
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "it will be better to let Nigeria resolve her
own problems internally" and that destabilizing Nigeria will not
be in the interest of Western nations.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking Wednesday on the Hausa Service of the British
Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) Alhaji Wada Nas, the special
adviser to Nigerian leader General Sani Abacha, blamed the
anti-Abacha demonstration in Ibadan on hostility of the U.S. and
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The hostility against Nigeria, he said, is not because of lack
of democracy or human rights, but because the Americans have a
hidden agenda, which would one day come to light.  
</P>
