<HEADLINE> S. African Envoy Lobbies US Senate on African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- South African ambassador to
the United States has written to all 100 U.S. senators to correct
the widespread impression that Pretoria is hostile to the African
Growth and Opportunity Bill.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa supports passage (of the bill)," ambassador
Franklin Sonn wrote, adding that "for the first time there has
been a real attempt by the U.S. congress to bring legislative
focus onto Africa and to recognize Africa as an important part of
the global economy", Business Day reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bill has been passed by the U.S. House of Representatives
but it is still under the scrutiny of the senate.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference with visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton in March, South African President Nelson Mandela called
the legislation "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki also said Africa does not welcome
the bill, which replaces aid with trade.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the bill, including labor unions and the U.S.
textile industry, have been exploiting these remarks as part of
their campaign to derail the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Sonn said South Africa was "particularly" in favor of
provisions extending duty free treatment to African textiles and
clothing and expanding the range of other African goods granted
preferential access to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also "appreciates" the bill's support for African
debt relief and for using U.S, government debt guarantees to help
launch private investment funds for African projects.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had only criticized the bill's "conditionalities", and
had emphasized that they remained "a subject for ongoing
discussion", Sonn said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
