<HEADLINE> Daimler, Chrysler Reach Merger Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest industrial concern
Daimler-Benz AG and the third-largest U.S. automaker Chrysler have
closed a merger deal that will create the world's third largest
carmaker, the two companies announced Thursday in Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
The merged company, to be known as DaimlerChrysler and worth
about 130 billion U.S. dollars, will be jointly headed by Daimler
chief Juergen Schrempp and his Chrysler counterpart Robert Eaton,
they said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the merger deal, Daimler will hold 57 percent of the new
company's shares while Chrysler 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
The deal, however, has still to be approved by shareholders of
both companies as well as anti-trust authorities.
</P>
<P>
Schrempp and Eaton are due to hold a joint press conference in
London on Thursday afternoon to give more details on the
deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
