<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Face-to-Face Talk With Ranariddh No Obstacle:Hun Sen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cambodian Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen said Thursday that face-to-face meeting between
him and former Cambodian first prime minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh is just a question of time.
</P>
<P>
"There is no obstacle for that (the meeting)," Hun Sen said at
a press conference held in Bangkok Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said that it is not hard for him and Ranariddh to work
with each other since they have had relations before.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian prime minister said that they need to cooperate
not only for the upcoming election but also for the future of
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said he "would not close all the door" in the political
field, but will "only close the door to the khmere rouge
hard-liners."
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether Ranariddh had to abandon his title of
first prime minister before their meeting, Hun Sen said during
their talks through telephone, Ranariddh never requested to meet
him as the first prime minister, but as the one who used to work
with him.
</P>
<P>
"I would not agree with a meeting with the prime minister,
which in this way will create two governments in Cambodia," Hun
Sen said.
</P>
<P>
"But i can accept the meeting (with Ranariddh) as the person I
used to work together, or in the individual capacity, or of one
party to another, or as one party leader with the prime minister,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
For the upcoming election scheduled on July 26, Hun Sen
stressed that the election must be held as planned.
</P>
<P>
"There would not be any delay to the election, and if there is
any delay, it would be next five years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also proposed three options to use state-owned and
private-owned radio stations so that all political parties in
Cambodia can be given equal access to the electronic media.
</P>
<P>
He also warned all foreign media broadcasting in Cambodian
language to remain neutral during the election.
</P>
<P>
Concerning refugees in Thailand, Hun Sen said it is the target
of his government to let them return to place they would like to
return, especially before the election.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen refused to forecast the result of the election, saying
the result will be known after counting all the votes.
</P>
<P>
However, he said if his Cambodian People's Party (CPP) wins, he
will organize a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
And if the CPP loses, he would also be pleased to transfer
power peacefully and join the coalition government if invited, or
stay opposition if not.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, who came here Wednesday for a two-day visit, will meet
Thai New Aspiration Party leader, former prime minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh later Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
