<HEADLINE> UNITA Urged to Observe Peace Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The international community has
urged the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) to cooperate with the government in the peace process in
the country, a senior U.S. official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Donald Steinberg, the U.S. Ambassador and one of the
representatives of the international observer nations to the
Angolan peace progress, said here that the international
community are "deeply concerned" over UNITA's refusal to observe
the Lusaka peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting between the international observers
and the Government representatives, Steinberg said that UNITA,
whose uncooperative attitudes have made it impossible to
accomplish the new timetable for implementing the peace process
by the end of March as scheduled, is still occupying some
"sensitive areas" like central Angola's Bailundo and Andulo.
</P>
<P>
He said that the international community is losing its
patience about these.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Faustino Muteka, head of the government mission to
the joint peace process committee, said on the same day that the
re-establishement of government institutions in the UNITA
controlled areas should be given top priority.
</P>
<P>
Though major progress has been made in the past months, he
said, some important tasks are still to be accomplished. He urged
that UNITA should move its headquarters to the capital city,
Luanda, as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jonas Savimbi, the UNITA leader had refused to
move into the residence the government prepared for him in
Luanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
