<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Increases in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's trade surplus
increased by a significant 49.2 percent to 3.72 billion ringgit
(about 1 billion U.S. dollars) in March this year from 2.5 billion
ringgit (675.675 million dollars) in February as a result of a
much faster growth in exports.
</P>
<P>
The March trade surplus represented an increase of 112.4
percent increase over the same month last year, the Statistics
Department said in its external trade summary for March 1998
released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bigger surplus was due to a much faster export growth of
31.2 percent to 24.501 billion ringgit (6.621 billion dollars) in
March from the year ago level, compared with a slower 22.8 percent
growth in imports of 20.778 billion ringgit (5.615 billion
dollars), it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, if trade in lumpy items, namely,
aircraft and ships/tankers, including their accessories, were
excluded from the import and re-export data, an impressive trade
surplus of 4.9 billion ringgit (1.324 billion dollars) would be
recorded in March.
</P>
<P>
Cumulatively, Malaysia's external trade balance registered a
favorable surplus of 8.8 billion ringgit (2.378 billion dollars)
during the first quarter compared with the 2.0 billion ringgit
(540.54 million dollars) in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
This was due to a substantial growth of 42.5 percent in exports
and a lower rate of growth at 29.9 percent in imports.
</P>
<P>
Total exports and imports for the January-March period were
69.8 billion ringgit (18.864 billion dollars) and 61.0 billion
ringgit (16.486 billion dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
With the exclusion of imports and re-exports of lumpy items,
Malaysia's trade balance during the first quarter would be in
surplus of 11.0 billion ringgit (2.972 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, the department said, electrical and
electronic products continued to be Malaysia's largest commodity
export earner, with total export earnings sharing 52.6 percent of
the country's total export revenue.
</P>
<P>
Palm oil was the second largest export earner, which accounted
for 5.6 percent of total exports.
</P>
<P>
Exports of liquefied natural gas (LNG) accounted for 3.8
percent of total exports, showing an increase by 52.7 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter, the department said the major categories
of imports by end-use comprised intermediate goods, capital goods
and consumption goods.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's major trading partners were the United States, Japan
and Singapore, with these three countries accounting for more than
half or 52.3 percent of Malaysia's total trade during the
January-March period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Region Plans Compulsory Education Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The central government will spend
290 million yuan (35 million U.S. dollars) to help nine
poverty-stricken counties in northwest China's Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region develop compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
The nine counties make up 45 percent of Ningxia's population
and 66.6 percent of its size.
</P>
<P>
To date, 11 of the 23 counties and cities in Ningxia have
completely carried out the nine-year compulsory education
requirement, providing a chance to attend school for 96.7 percent
of school-age children.
</P>
<P>
A local educational official said that the investment will be
used to build new schools, repair campus buildings, buy books and
teaching equipment, and hold training programs for teachers.
</P>
<P>
The investment is part of the country's largest compulsory
education project in poor areas, which will spend a total of 2.4
billion yuan to carry out compulsory education nationwide by
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
