<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Opposition Seeks Alliance in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest
opposition party, the National Party (NP), has reiterated its
call on opposition parties to fight next year's general election
on a joint platform, newspapers published here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NP leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk urged Wednesday small
parties to join his party's fight to prevent the African National
Congress (ANC) from obtaining a two-thirds majority in the
election, which would enable the ANC to change clauses in the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Pretoria that this could be done if
opposition parties stopped wasting energy by fighting one
another.
</P>
<P>
A two-thirds majority for the ANC would spell grave danger for
democracy, as the ANC had already indicated it might reconsider
the position of the Reserve Bank, scrap the property clause in
the constitution and get rid of watchdog institutions such as the
auditor-general, Van Schalkwyk said.
</P>
<P>
It was of crucial importance that opposition parties put their
resources, financial and otherwise, together to fight the ANC, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The ANC at this stage had budgeted some 150 million Rand (30
million U.S. Dollars) for its election campaign, while the NP's
maximum would be about 40 million Rand (8 million Dollars), he
said.
</P>
<P>
Van Schalkwyk said the NP would seek a possible alliance with
the Democratic Party, the Freedom Front, both white-based
parties, and the Inkatha Freedom Party, the biggest black
opposition party, because their policy frameworks were in line
with that of the NP.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation would entail a loose coalition between these
parties based on a joint manifesto, and aimed at giving all
leaders equal status, he said.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, a close coalition such as the ruling alliance
of the ANC, South African Communist Party (SACP) and the Congress
of South African Trade Unions (COSATU), was not viable as smaller
opposition parties might be afraid of being absorbed, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pan Africanist Congress and the United Democratic
Movement would not be considered as they "were too far away from
us", Van Schalkwyk said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
