<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Air Force, Navy To Enforce Ban on Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China will send air force and navy
units to the South China Sea to enforce the ban on fishing from
May 15 to September 10.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with Chinese laws on marine waste dumping and
fishing, the joint inspection team also will enforce regulations
on maritime utilization and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The air force will make inspection flights in the east and west
coastal waters off Guangdong Province as well as the Zhujiang
River delta area, according to sources with the maritime aquatic
department in south China's Guangdong Province and the South China
Sea Branch of the National Bureau of Oceanography.
</P>
<P>
If an illegal activity is spotted, inspection ships will be
dispatched to the target marine space.
</P>
<P>
The inspections have been necessary to counter serious problems
in excessive, unpaid and disorderly utilization of maritime
resources near Guangdong in recent years, authorities said. The
province expects this round of law enforcement to dispose of a
number of serious violators in its coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998 is the international oceanic year. The inspection
will help bring maritime resources under closer governmental
administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Spending More on Housing, Electronic Goods, and Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Consumer spending is up in China,
and housing, electronic goods, and travel are popular items,
industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
According to people at a seminar on consumer trends here
recently, at least 60 million urban families have no housing of
their own and the average living space in two-thirds of China's
cities is below the national average.
</P>
<P>
But, savings deposits have grown to 4 trillion yuan (481.9
billion US dollars), and there is 30 billion yuan in housing funds
available, increasing home buying power.
</P>
<P>
So, in order to improve housing conditions, the Chinese
government has removed some housing construction charges and has
called for a better installment-buying system and is working out a
housing reform.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that a home buying enthusiasm could last
until the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, electronics and information technology goods have
been growing by 27.5 percent annually, with telephones and
computers being the two hottest items and analysts say that demand
is expected to remain high.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, home appliances will remain strong in coming
years. It is expected that over the next five years, rural areas
will need 140 million more refrigerators, 160 million color
televisions, and 166 million washing machines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
