<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Invests in China's Tea Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese company has set up a
joint venture to produce Japanese-style green tea in the Dabie
mountainous area in geographical conditions usually avoided by
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, the Henan Xinlin Tea Co. Ltd., has delivered
its initial production to market. The company, with an investment
of 2.9 million U.S. dollars, is located in Xinxian County in
central China's Henan Province, traditionally renowned for its
tea-growing.
</P>
<P>
Haramo Yasinao, president of the Tokyo Huayu Company, the
Japanese partner, recently expressed his confidence in the
company's success and pledged that the green tea, produced with
Japanese equipment and techniques, will be among the best in China.
</P>
<P>
"Although the region is relatively impoverished and isolated
from the outside world, we treasure its abundant tea resources and
diligent and modest local laborers," he said. "We believe the
project will be mutually beneficial to both parties."
</P>
<P>
To date, 101 foreign-funded companies have been established in
the Dabie mountainous areas, where late military strategists Liu
Bocheng and Deng Xiaoping based their forces against the
Nationalist government headed by Chiang Kai-shek during the civil
war (1946-1949).
</P>
<P>
The region has attracted more than 80 million U.S. dollars in
contracted foreign investment to its light industry, processing of
agricultural products, catering and mineral resource development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Balance of Payments Posts Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Governor of Central Bank of the
Philippines Gabriel Singson announced Thursday that the country's
balance of payments posted a 1.8 billion-U.S.-dollar surplus as of
mid-April this year.
</P>
<P>
This represented a 380 percent increase over the year-ago level
of 367 million U.S. dollars. Preliminary reports said the surplus
mainly came from an improving trade position and loan inflows,
Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Balance of payments was the difference between a nation's
payments to foreign countries and its total receipts from foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months this year, the Philippines'
merchandise exports grew by 24 percent to 6.82 billion dollars,
further narrowing down the country's trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
During the first two weeks of April, a total of 1.24 billion
dollars flew into the country, including a 750-million-dollar
Paris Club loan from a consortium of foreign banks and the
proceeds of the national government's bond flotation amounting to
5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, international investors' confidence in the local
economy was regained, witnessed by the net inflow of 400 million
dollars in portfolio investments during the period, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
With these developments, the central bank's gross international
reserves stood at 10.8 billion dollars as of mid-April, equivalent
to 2.5 months of imports of goods and services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets up Large Farm-Produce Wholesale Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Farm Produce Wholesale
Market started operation recently in the city's Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
The new market, which was built at a cost of 130 million yuan,
is one of China's five state-level wholesale markets for
agricultural produce. Its first phase covers an area of 12
hectares, with a trading floor of 40,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale market, which has already attracted more than 300
clients, also includes a customer service center, a settlement
center and freezing storehouses, among other facilities.
</P>
<P>
Designers say that the wholesale market will cover a total area
of 32 hectares when construction is completed.
</P>
<P>
The market will adopt internationally advanced trading
practices, such as bidding and auction, and will eventually be
linked with other major markets worldwide, according to Zhu
Wenzhao, the market's deputy general manager.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
