<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Further Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued falling in
Tokyo Thursday in tandem with a fall in the Japanese yen and the
yield on long-term Japanese government bonds.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 100.81 points or 0.66
percent from Wednesday's close to 15,143.03.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 10.79 points or 0.90 percent to
1,189.87.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section remained thin at an estimated 360
million shares, almost unchanged from Wednesday's 350 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Motor was Thursday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Nikkei index tested the 15,000 line just after
seeing the U.S. dollar hit a high of 133.65 yen around noon, up
more than 1 yen from Wednesday's levels.
</P>
<P>
The yield on the key 10-year government bond, meanwhile,
registered yet another record low of 1.355 percent in the
afternoon, reflecting the widespread pessimism about the course of
the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Tokyo market sentiment was also dampened by
morning drops in other Asian markets, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,329 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced gainers 760 to 364, with 151 remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
