<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Re-Write History Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The ruling African National
Congress (ANC) of South Africa will rewrite the country's past
and correct the mistakes of four decades of apartheid
historiography.
</P>
<P>
Nhlanhla Ndebele, a 30-year-old graduate of Wits University,
has been appointed to research the ANC's massive archive, the
Star daily quoted parliament Speaker Frene Ginwala as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the appointment as "historic", Ginwala said "the
ANC has brought its archives back to South Africa. Part of the
project is to build a common understanding of our past."
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Sibusiso Bengu was also quoted as saying
that the study would mark a fresh step in the creation of a new
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South Africa led by President Nelson Mandela and his
Government of National Unity, abolished in 1994 apartheid which
dominated for decades in the country.
</P>
<P>
Ndebele, who was supposed to spend three years to finish
researching the ANC archives, said he hoped his work would be the
starting point for further study into South Africa's bloodstained
past. This project "will change the way history is taught in our
schools," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ANC archives, scattered all over the world when the
organization was in exile for years, were established at Fort
Hare University in the Eastern Cape Province two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
