<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Photographer Comments on Changes in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- "Unbelievable changes have taken
place in China, compared with what I saw during my last trip to
the country 20 years ago," reports Stig T. Karlsson, a 68-year-old
Swedish photographer.
</P>
<P>
In the late 70s, Mr. Karlsson visited India, Japan, and China
and marveled at China's well-organized society and human
interests, and later published a book about his Asia trip,
entitled "At Home In China".
</P>
<P>
Karlsson is making a 20-day visit to China now at the
invitation of the Chinese Ministry of Culture and started in
Guangdong Province in the south, where he was surprised at the
changes in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
"China's villages have developed to such an unbelievably high
level," he says, commenting on how traditional and uncreative
Chinese farmers used to be.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, Karlsson visited the home of Zhang Maogen, a
retired steel plant worker. During his first visit, he had stayed
with Zhang's family for seven days. This time he spent three days
with them, taking pictures of their daily life.
</P>
<P>
He says he's happy to see that Zhang's family has so many
modern electric appliances, and that the couple's warm feelings
and kindness towards others remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
One thing that attracted him most in China was the vividness of
Shanghai, and he says he feels at home when he's in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
However, he says he's worried about the large number of
skyscrapers there and wonders whether the city government will
protect old buildings, since so many new buildings have
appeared. And he wonders whether the city's industries and traffic
will pollute the environment, pointing to the fact that the city's
air is not as clean as it was 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Mr. Karlsson revisited India and Japan and he is
planning another album on Asia, but with China as the main theme
still.
</P>
<P>
"I will come back to China after 20 years, when I am 88 years
old," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
