<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Coffee Exports Drop for Bad Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's coffee exports have
dropped dramatically due to bad weather, slashing the country's
export income and inflicting a heavy blow to the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released Wednesday by the Uganda
Coffee Development Authority, the coffee exports in the last
seven months totaled 1.54 million bags (60-kilo) valued at 147.4
million U.S. Dollars, a decline of 48 percent in volume and 36
percent in value compared with the same period of the last export
year.
</P>
<P>
April witnessed an export of 138,264 bags of coffee with a
value of 24.2 million Dollars, nearly 50 percent down from last
April's 268,825 bags.
</P>
<P>
While the unit value remains relatively stable, torrential
rains brought by the El-Nino phenomenon were usually blamed for
the sharp cut in coffee export.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is uganda's single largest foreign exchange earner. It
accounted for 68 and 56 percents of total exports in the last two
years respectively.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997 was close to 6
billion Dollars and its total export earnings were 622 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The overall fall in exports in tandem with the decline on the
cumulative basis partly explains the weakening of the Ugandan
Shilling against the U.S. Dollar during April. The exchange rate
between Dollar and the Ugandan Shilling declined from 1:1100 to
1:1275 at the end of April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
