<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia, Botswana Agree to Peaceful Solution for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibia and Botswana, locked
in a territorial dispute involving islands in the Linyanti-Chobe
river, Wednesday initialled an accord indicating they would opt
for a diplomatic solution, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from both countries met behind closed doors
on Tuesday and Wednesday, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's major daily newspaper, The Namibian, reported that
the delegates were mandated by their governments to hammer out an
agreement to establish a joint delimitation commission.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Namibian delegation, Albert Kawana, told reporters
that there was an agreement a long time ago between the two
governments to come to a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
The two governments must still sign the agreement before it is
ratified in parliament, while the two countries will have to
agree on a date on which the agreement will be signed by top
officials.
</P>
<P>
A joint commission will have to demarcate the entire stretch
along the Linyanti-Chobe river, comprising about 350 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are disputing Kasikili Island, which is
called Sedudu in Botswana, and the island of Situngu.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has stationed a number of troops on both islands.
</P>
<P>
Tensions grew on the island of Situngu late last year when a
Botswana Defense Force unit allegedly trooped on the island and
harassed Namibian villagers farming there.
</P>
<P>
The Kasikili dispute will be heard before the International
Court of Justice in The Hague early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
