<HEADLINE> Jones Faces Tough Challenge from Li Xuemei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- American world champion Marion Jones
is facing a tough challenge from well tuned-up host Li Xuemei in
the world fastest woman 100 meters race starting next Tuesday in
China's northwestern city Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old multi talented American, a
basketballer-turned-sprinter, has to fight Li tooth and nail in
the unprecedented commecial race for women sprinters if she wants
to retain the title of the world 100-meter queen.
</P>
<P>
Li, who surprised the world last year with a 10.79-second run,
the second fastest time in the world last season to Jones' 10.76,
tuned up her shape brilliantly by registering the year's world
best of 11.01 at a national Grand Prix meeting in her hometown
Chengdu on April 18.
</P>
<P>
But Jones, who won the 100-meter title at last year's world
championships and clocked 6.95 in the 60 meters two months ago,
the year's world best, also has showed that she is in a superb
form after long jumping a fabulous 7.05-meter early this week in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever wants to win the showdown, she has to romp home in a
sub-11-second dash, " Li's coach Zhang Rongwei said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese Athletics Association, the organizer
of the race, Olympic champion Gail Devers will skep the race, and
Zhanna Pintussevich of Ukraine, world 100-meter silver medal
winner last year, also withdrew from the duel with a last minute
decision.
</P>
<P>
The other world class foreign sprinters due to compete are
Savatheda Fynes of Bahamas, last year's world bronze medal winner,
Chandra Sturrup of Bahamas, the 1996 Olympic 100-meter fourth
finisher with a personal best of 11 seconds, and Carlette Guidry,
a member of the U.S. 4x100m relay winning team at the 1996
Olympics with a 10.94 personal best. All the four foreign dashers
are based in the United States and trained by Amerian coaches.
</P>
<P>
Susanthika Jayashinghe of Sri Lanka, the world 200m runner-up
who was tested positive last month, was kicked out of the IAAF
sunctioned race.
</P>
<P>
Jones will fly to Chengdu on May 10 after completing an IAAF
Grand Prix meet in Japan this Saturday. The race will be held in
a 30,000-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the appearence fee for Jones is about
45,000 U.S dollars. Whoever breaks the world record will gain
100,000 U.S. dollars as a bonus.
</P>
<P>
The race will start at 16:20 local time following preluding
exhibition events including the men's and women's sprint hurdles
and 400 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
