<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Defines New Criteria of Model Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Even in the 1950s and '60s, the model workers were encouraged
to combine hard work with ingenuity. Now the latter has
undoubtedly carried greater weight," said Su Neng, head of the
department in charge of appointing model workers under the
All-China Federation of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
This change of criteria has mirrored social progress in China,
and is in line with the Chinese government's principle of
"revitalizing the country through science and education," he added.
</P>
<P>
Another conspicuous figure in this year's top 10 model workers
is Zhang Weidong, a construction worker from Anshan City in
northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
A former laid-off worker, the 51-year-old Zhang is the sole
representative in the top 10 of workers in the northeastern China,
a traditional industrial base which is home to a large proportion
of the country's state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In March of 1992, Zhang, then head of a tilers' squad in a
state-owned construction firm, voluntarily applied for a layoff to
help the 32 other laid-off workers from his firm to find a new way
of living. Now they are running a housing decoration company with
annual profits of more than 300,000 yuan (about 36,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Zhang's action has shown the Chinese workers' understanding
of, support for and active participation in the reforms. It has
also reflected the working class' lofty spirit of sharing the
worries and burdens of the country, which is most needed in our
time," Su said.
</P>
<P>
A new social group that has emerged since the early 1990s with
the deepening of reforms in the state enterprises, China's
laid-off workers now total 8.6 million according to the latest
official statistics. It has become a common concern of the
government and the society to provide them with new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Media reports show that this year across China, many former
laid-off workers who have scored success in their new jobs won the
titles of model workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Grows in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in Jiangsu
Province, east China, has grown rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the province had more than 1.36
million households engaging in industrial and commercial
activities at the end of last year, with 2.34 million people and
combined capital of 11.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that there were 69,943 private
enterprises at the end of last year, employing 670,000
people and having 32.2 billion yuan in registered capital.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangsu provincial government in recent years has placed
great importance on creating a level playing field for the private
economy and has taken steps to eliminate unreasonable fees.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector has also been involved, giving support to
private or individually-run businesses.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Jiangsu's private sector has grown significantly
in recent years. In the city of Xishan, for example, there are 30
private enterprises with yearly sales of more than 10 million yuan
each.  
</P>
</TEXT>
