<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Chilean Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen said that
China will make joint efforts with Chile to establish a
cross-century, long-term, stable and cooperative bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remark here this morning in a meeting with
visiting Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his pleasure at meeting again with his "old
friend," as the two have met many times since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that since China and Chile established diplomatic
ties 28 years ago bilateral friendship and cooperation in
politics, economy and trade, science and technology and culture
have steadily advanced, and the two sides have also cooperated in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said that both China and Chile are APEC members and
important countries along the Pacific Ocean, and they have made
remarkable achievements in economic construction and social
progress in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should be, and are, completely able to make
contributions to peace and development of the world and the
region, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said his current visit to China is part of bilateral
high-level exchanges, and the two countries have cooperated
smoothly in various aspects such as politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chilean government highly values bilateral
relations and works for further development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Insulza reiterated Chile's "one China" position, which was
appreciated by Qian.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed Insulza on China's stance on the Taiwan
question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
