<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Pushing Economic Growth In Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Shanghai has asked the industrial sector to increase investment
and exports in the second quarter to offset the negative effects
of the Asian financial crisis and to ensure 10-percent industrial
growth for the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output here rose 8.9 percent in the first four
months of the year, compared with a year ago and exports of 14
major machinery and electronics products was 284 million US
dollars in the first three months, up 6.97 percent from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Southeast Asia, Japan, and the Republic of Korea
(ROK) were down a great deal. Exports of metallurgical products to
Japan and the ROK were down 40 percent and exports of steel to
Southeast Asia dropped 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Large imports of low-priced industrial raw materials like
chemicals and fertilizers for farm use affected industrial
production in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
And businesses in Shanghai have been asked to adjust their
product mix, develop different products, and increase the supply
of marketable goods.
</P>
<P>
The city will also look for new markets in Africa, the Middle
East, Europe, and Africa and change its export strategy and will
build more high-tech production centers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens New Air Route Between Jiangxi, Guizhou Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- An air route linking central
China's Jiangxi Province and southwestern Guizhou Province began
service today.
</P>
<P>
The new route, which ended the record of no direct air flights
between Jiangxi and Guizhou, actually starts in Nanjing, capital
of east China's Jiangsu Province, extends to Nanchang, capital of
Jiangxi Province, and ends in Guizhou, capital of Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
The air route will help enhance regional cooperation and
economic contact between the more-developed east China and the
under-developed southwest areas, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Turning Eroded Land into Orchards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The gentle green mountains around the
town of Hetian in western Fujian Province, east China, would
hardly make a person think of it by its previous name -- Flaming
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
It had got that name because of the reddish eroded earth on it
and was one of the country's most serious victims of water
erosion, with 44.6 percent of its land, or 15,800 ha., in that
state. An 18-year-old pine tree there would only grow one meter
high.
</P>
<P>
The serious deterioration of the environment had resulted in
equally stubborn poverty and a per capita annual income of 106
yuan in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, however, things there have gradually changed after
a large program was started to control water erosion. Every year,
the provincial government has since allocated 200,000 yuan for
the project.
</P>
<P>
A decade of planting and soil improvements has recovered 10,000
ha. of eroded land, or 60 percent of the destroyed coverage. Soil
erosion at Hetian is basically under control and annual soil
losses are down from 8,590 tons per sq. km. to 449 tons.
</P>
<P>
Fruit trees have also been planted in an area of 6,700 ha., on
which chickens are also raised.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the town's per capita annual income was up to 2,700,
well above the country's poverty line of 500 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
