<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, May 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has proposed
establishing diplomatic ties between Yugoslavia and Bosnia
immediately and unconditionally, the Oslobodenje daily circulated
in Sarajevo reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Milosevic's proposal was delivered Monday by
Milorad Dodik, the prime minister of the Serb Republic of
Bosnia-Herzegovina, to Alija Izetbegovic, the chairman of the
Bosnian Presidency. Under the proposal, Yugoslavia "respects the
sovereignty and the integrity of Bosnia-Herzegovina" while
"Bosnia-Herzegovina respects Yugoslavia's right of inheritance."
(Bosnia-Yugoslavia-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will continue to encourage
Japan to make a greater effort to resolve its economic problems in
order to enhance global economic growth, a Clinton administration
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told a press briefing that
he expected Japan's problems to be a central part of the economic
discussions at meetings of finance officials this weekend in
London and next week when U.S. President Bill Clinton and leaders
of other major industrial countries gather for their annual
economic summit. (US-G-7 Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's newly-appointed central bank Governor
Chatumongol Sonakul has committed himself to reducing foreign
debts and easing the cash squeeze for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol hinted that interest rates would remain high as
they are the best defense against national debts and liquidity
crisis, the Bangkok Post reported Thursday. (Thailand-Bank-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia Wednesday promised to follow the
standards set by the European Union on the rights for ethnic
minorities while solving all outstanding issues in the Serbian
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference with visiting Swedish
Foreign Minister Lena Hielm Valen, Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivorad Jovanovic also reiterated that all disputes in Kosovo
should be settled through political means within the context of
Serbia. But he said that no separatist or terrorist activities
are allowed. (Yugoslavia-Sweden-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
