<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Defines New Criteria of Model Workers(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Around this year's May Day, the
Chinese news media acquainted the public with a new hero -- Wang
Tao, an auto mechanic from central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Wang, 42, ranked first on the list of China's newly appointed
"National Top 10 Outstanding Workers," the country's paramount
honor for urban laborers.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, Wang worked extremely hard with no
complaints, and was always ready to help his fellow workers or
clients. He certainly shared all typical virtues of the previous
national model workers China had appointed since the founding of
the People's Republic in 1949.
</P>
<P>
What makes Wang different from his predecessors is that, in his
decades-long efforts to perfect his skills, he invented a unique
method of operation, which was later introduced to all mechanics
in the Dongfeng Motor Company, one of China's leading car makers
and Wang's employer.
</P>
<P>
However, Wang's most impressive achievement is that, with only
a high school education, he wrote two technical books on
automobile maintenance of 200,000 words.
</P>
<P>
"As a worker, you need to work conscientiously," Wang
said. "And for a worker living in the new period, it's not enough
to contribute only your physical labor, you must also use your
brain and always seek to improve yourself."
</P>
<P>
According to a Beijing sociologist, the wide publicity Wang
received recently reflects the Chinese government's higher demands
on the quality of industrial workers as the country's reform and
opening-up drive is now opening a new chapter.
</P>
<P>
"In today's world, the survival and development of enterprises
are mainly decided by science and technology," the sociologist
said. "China is eager to encourage its workers to constantly
improve their educational and technical levels, and show
creativity and a pioneering spirit while working diligently, so as
to help add vitality to, and raise the competitiveness of, the
industrial sector."
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, workers that only know hard work and
thrift, who used to be popular candidates for the honor of model
worker under China's planned economy from the 1950s to the early
1980s, are now giving way to those who have displayed technical
competence, creativity or a good command of modern science and
technology in their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
