<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Passes Test of Financial Crisis: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here
Thursday that Hong Kong has "passed the test" of a financial
crisis that has affected Asia since last July.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing annual Corporate Conference of Asia
Society, Tung said 1997 was an extraordinary year for Asia at
large when structural weaknesses of some Asian nations triggered
the financial crisis that reverberated around the world.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive noted that those economies that have sound
fundamentals, credible policies and low leverage, such as China,
have succeeded in weathering the storm. "Those with free markets,
strong regulations, rule of law and stringent fiscal discipline,
such as Hong Kong and Singapore, have passed the test."
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Asia has been painful but the
fundamentals in Asia have not changed, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to prudent fiscal management, Tung said, Hong Kong's
foreign exchange reserves stood at 92.8 billion U.S. dollars at
the end of 1997 -- the third largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
"These huge reserves provide not just 100 percent, not just 200
percent, but 800 percent backing for the currency in circulation,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he did not believe Hong Kong needs to devalue the HK
dollar, saying, "It is not in the interest of Hong Kong to do so."
</P>
<P>
The fact is that the total value of Hong Kong's trade in goods
and services in a year is equal to well over 250 percent of its
GDP, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Tung pointed out that the SAR government is "conscious
of the high costs although Hong Kong does not wish to become more
competitive through devaluation." To tackle these problems, the
government has planned a series of measures which were announced
in Tung's Policy Speech delivered on October 8 last year.
</P>
<P>
Tung admitted that as a result of several attacks on the Hong
Kong dollar in the past few months, interest rates have gone up
and remained relatively high. This has resulted in a slowdown in
economic growth, an increase in the unemployment rate and a
decline in the stock and property markets.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "we are not allowing the Asian financial
turmoil to derail our long-term focus of building a Hong Kong
which is fair, free, prosperous and economically competitive."
</P>
<P>
The government is able to continue with its massive plan of
investment in infrastructure and education which will make Hong
Kong much more efficient and competitive in the 21st century, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
