<HEADLINE> Guangxi's Coastal Cities Developing Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Coastal cities in the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region have been developing fast and becoming outlets
for southwestern China in the opening up process.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the Chinese government decided to turn
Guangxi into a passage to the sea and now, cities like Beihai,
Qinzhou, and Fangcheng are the points connecting southwestern
China's economy with Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Guangxi government spent a lot on infrastructure in those
three cities, building expressways, railways, airport, roads, and
waterways.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in their economy and investment environment has
attracted investors from the neighbouring provinces of Sichuan,
Yunnan, and Guizhou, and from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Beihai developed from a sleepy town into a medium-sized city
with its GDP reaching 11.2 billion yuan last year. It has also had
growth in its ocean economy and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Qinzhou became a new port city with 46 overseas-funded projects
worth 769 million US dollars and had a GDP of 12.7 billion yuan in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Fangcheng has become one of the largest ports in southern
China, handling 6.5 million tons of goods every year, accounting
for 70 percent of Guangxi's total. Its trade with Vietnam was
worth two billion yuan last year and accounted for half of the
total of the country trade with Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
