<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt's Overspending Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce (ZNCC) has said it is perturbed about the public
sector's continued show of financial mismanagement coupled by
propensity to borrow heavily on the domestic money market.
</P>
<P>
ZNCC Chief Executive Wonder Maisiri said Wednesday it was
apparent that the government created opportunities for itself to
spend money which the country could "ill afford" given the
turbulent economic situation facing the country, a report from
the Zimbabwe News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark while responding to the Auditor General's
Report for the 1995/96 financial year, which revealed the
government exceeded its borrowing limits by 72.8 billion
Zimbabwean Dollars (4.3 billion U.S. Dollars) without
parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
He said in heavily borrowing on the domestic market, the
government was crowding out the private sector, which is
struggling to make ends meet and to sustain businesses due to
punitive high inflation and commercial interest rates.
</P>
<P>
He said revelations by the Auditor General's Report that
ministries were not respecting the parliament's authority by
overspending were a depressing scenario.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Zimbabwe will await impatiently to see what
punishment will be metted out by parliament to the offending
ministries," he said, "this indeed smacks of bad governance which
can hardly be condoned by our economically ailing society."
</P>
<P>
"What is equally staggering and embarrassing is the lack of
transparency in the matter in which public funds collected by
ministries are not accounted for," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
