<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Quarter Work Key to Economic Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Economic work for the second quarter
of 1998 is of vital importance for China to meet this year's 8
percent growth in its gross domestic product (GDP), the People's
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
China had a 7.2 percent GDP growth rate during the first
quarter, 2.2 percentage points lower than the same period last
year. To hit this year's projected economic growth target, GDP
increases for the other three quarters must be higher than 8
percent, the paper quoted sources at the State Development
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The greatest potential to promote rapid economic growth this
year lies in investments, which should be put into place as soon
as possible as the results can only be felt in the latter half of
the year, the paper reported in a signed article.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, priorities should be given to:
</P>
<P>
-- Speeding up projects already under construction;
</P>
<P>
-- Trying to complete feasibility studies and preparations for
newly approved projects, and get them started within the year;
</P>
<P>
-- Selecting some marketable and efficient products and
enterprises, and increasing investments for equipment replacement;
</P>
<P>
-- Treating medium- and small-size businesses and township
enterprises the same as state-owned ones in terms of offering
credit loans and other services; and,
</P>
<P>
-- Carrying out policies that aim to increase exports, such as
credit loans to support exports of complete sets of equipment and
labor contracts, and export tax refunds.
</P>
<P>
However, the commission warns that a down-to-earth manner is
necessary in this effort to avoid inefficient high-speed growth
and a bubble economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
