<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genetic Engineering Producing Hardier Tomatos for Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have developed a
better kind of the tomato by splicing genetic material from a
cold-water fish with the pollen of tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
After ten years of research, they have gotten tomato seeds with
greater resistance to cold than ordinary ones. The sprouted plants
were found to be capable of surviving for six hours at four
degrees below zero Celsius in experiments. Further experiments
showed that the seeds can be planted 15 days earlier than ordinary
seeds in the spring and can survive a late frost, which kills
ordinary tomato plants.
</P>
<P>
And the harvest season of these tomatos can last a month longer
than that of ordinary ones.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yong, who was in charge of the research in Harbin, the
capital of Heilongjiang Province, says that the new tomato plants
have high yields and the tomatos have a vitamin C content that is
15 percent greater than ordinary ones, and they taste better.
</P>
<P>
The seeds have become a best seller since they were approved by
government departments last year. They were sold for 200,000 yuan
(24,000 US dollars) per kilogram to an agricultural research
institute in Liaoning Province in northeastern China -- or twice
the price of gold. People keep coming to buy them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
