<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cervical Cancer Turns into Major Killer in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Long ignored cervical cancer is
turning into a major killer in sub-Saharan Africa, leading
thousands of women in child-bearing age to death, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The disease now is the leading cause of death in the cancer
diseases and the number of its victims is rising in sub-Saharan
Africa, medical experts were quoted as warning by Thursday's
Daily Nation newspaper.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 500,000 cases of cancer of the cervix
occur every year with 200,000 to 300,000 dying from the disease
annually worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Professor J.K. Mati, a cancer expert, says 80 percent of the
victims were in the developing countries with the peak age being
between 35 and 45 years old.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas in developed countries there has been a marked
reduction in the rates of mortality associated with cervical
cancer. In the last two to three decades, in the sub-Saharan
Africa, mortality remains high," he says.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase to late diagnosis and lack of
adequate equipment for successful treatment.
</P>
<P>
High illiteracy levels among women in Africa and rising
poverty have aggravated the already bad situation on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
"Cervical cancer mortality is higher among the poor, who lack
easy access to health facilities. Advanced cervical cancer is
more common among rural-based women," Mati says.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the risk of contracting the disease, he urges women
to avoid having multiple sexual partners and to give up smoking.
</P>
<P>
He says scientists have also discovered some relationship
between certain methods of contraceptive use and cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
"A slight association has been shown between oral
contraceptive use (the pill) and cervical cancer, the risk being
higher among women who had used the method for five or more
years," he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Kenyan Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
