<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Muslim, Croat Republics Asked to Stop Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Carlos Westendorp, the high
representative of the Peace Implementation Council, has asked the
former Muslim and Croat republics to stop immediately all their
government-style administrative activities.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp, who accused the already dissolved republics of
continuing these functions, made the demand in a briefing note to
other international organizations and all foreign embassies in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He said that according to a decision made on April 6, 1998 by
the Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation, the Croatian Republic of
Herzeg-Bosna and the former Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina
should cease all their functions, and legal documents issued by
the two entities were void.
</P>
<P>
The former Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina was established
by the Muslims in 1991 soon after the dissolution of the former
Yugoslavia. It was followed by the establishment of the Croatian
Republic of Herzeg-Bosnia and the Republic of Srpska. Civil war
broke out immediately among the three entities.
</P>
<P>
After the Dayton Agreement, which brought an end to the bloody
civil war, Bosnia become a united country with two entities,
namely the Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation and the Republic of
Srpska.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, after the establishment of the Bosnian
Muslim-Croat Federation and the unification of Bosnia, the former
Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina and the Croatian Republic of
Herzeg-Bosnia should have ceased to be.
</P>
<P>
But since both the Muslims and the Croatians fear that their
interests cannot be protected properly, they keep the republics
although they have ceased to exist by name. They accuse each other
of failing to abide by the Dayton Agreement.
</P>
<P>
A recent call from a Croatian leader for a federation of three
separate entities by the Croatians, Muslims and Serbs has caused
great unrest in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Named to NBA All-Defensive Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan Wednesday became the
first player in history to be selected to the National Basketball
Association All-Defensive First Team on nine occasions.
</P>
<P>
The league announced its All-Defensive First and Second Teams,
and Jordan passed Bobby Jones of Denver and Philadelphia for the
all-time record for most selections.
</P>
<P>
The Chicago Bulls superstar guard, who has also won a record 10
NBA scoring titles, led all players with 25 First-Team votes and
53 of a possible 56 points and was the only player named on the
maximum 28 ballots.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is joined on the First Team by Bulls teammate Scottie
Pippen, who earned his seventh selection at forward despite
missing nearly half the season after undergoing foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Jones are the only players with more First Team
selections than Pippen.
</P>
<P>
Guard Gary Payton of Seattle, center Dikembe Mutombo of
Atlanta, who was named the NBA Defensive Player of the Year for
the third time on Tuesday, and forward Karl Malone of Utah were
the other First Team selections.
</P>
<P>
The voting panel consisted of the 29 NBA head coaches, who were
not permitted to vote for players from their own team.
</P>
<P>
Payton was second to Jordan with 24 First Team votes and 51
points. Mutombo was third with 23 First Team votes and 48
points. This marks the fifth First Team selection for Payton and
the second for Mutombo and Malone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
