<HEADLINE> Uzbek President Satisfied with Talks with Russian Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Uzbek President Islam
Karimov Wednesday expressed here his satisfaction with talks with
Russian leaders on the bilateral relations, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Karimov, who arrived in Moscow on Tuesday for a three-day state
visit, had talks with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Karimov told a briefing that he and Russian
leaders reached several agreements which will create new powerful
momentum for the development of the two countries relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the results of the talks would hasten solutions to
"overdue issues in the economic and political and humanitarian
spheres and in the sphere of defending interests of Russia in
Central Asia."
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko said that it is crucially important that relations
between Russia and Uzbekistan are built on a clear understanding
of their economic interests, and not on attempts to substitute the
real economic interests by general talk about cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Russian prime minister said that the accords signed
Wednesday by the Russian and Uzbek sides will improve the trade
development of the two countries. The two countries' trade made
1.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 and increased by 21 percent in
the first quarter of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
