<HEADLINE> Asia Should Abandon Easy-going Way of Growth: Vietnamese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister
Pham Gia Khiem said here Thursday that Asian countries should
abandon the easy-going way of growth and continue economic reforms
and integration.
</P>
<P>
Pham said at the morning session of the on-going Ninth Annual
Corporate Conference of Asia Society that with the support of the
world community, the Asian countries will be able to get their
economies recovered soon in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the present conditions of the economic crisis
demand the governments and people of these countries ... on one
hand fully develop all economic potentials and comparative
advantages in human resources and on the other hand completely
abandon the easy-going way of growth, persistently continue
economic reforms and integration, combine domestic strength with
external assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, he added, "we shall be able to gradually get the
situation right and build up an Asia of more dynamic and
sustainable development based on a new foundation more adaptive to
changes as mankind enters the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese official said one of the very important
characteristics of Asian economy is its high domestic savings
rate, from 30 percent to 40 percent of GDP, a very decisive factor
to ensure capital supply for a high and stable economic
performance.
</P>
<P>
In spite of continuous high growth for years, Pham said, the
region's economies displayed structural weaknesses and serious
macroeconomic imbalances as evidenced by overvalued exchange
rates, capital-intensive and properties development projects with
low rate of return, and the domestic monetary and financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
Pham noted that removing the present obstacles does not only
call for the efforts of Asia alone, but also of the world
community, including the financial support of countries and
international financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
In a world of increasing globalization and interdependence with
growing shared interests, "we should and must work closely
together to overcome any hardship as it appears in the course of
development." he said.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the morning session of the conference, Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region reviewed the development of Hong Kong after its return to
China about 10 months ago and in the aftermath of the recent
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that "success is manifested everyday in Hong Kong"
after the handover and the region has "passed the test" of the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the session, President Mitsuo Sato of the
Asian Development Bank called for reforms of financial
institutions on a broad basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
