<HEADLINE> Vietnam Airlines Cuts Flights to Stem Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam Airlines has decided to cancel
or reduce flights on several international and domestic routes in
an attempt to stem its losses, a senior official of the
state-owned airlines said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The company will stop indefinitely its Hanoi-Manila service,
which was officially opened in 1987, although it is still
available for Philippines Airlines to fly on a cost-sharing basis.
</P>
<P>
Flights from Hanoi to Seoul and from Ho Chi Minh City to Seoul
will be reduced from four to two a week.
</P>
<P>
Hanoi-Hong Kong flights will be reduced from 11 to nine a week
and the Hanoi-Taipei route will be cut from five to three flights
a week.
</P>
<P>
Flights on four domestic routes are also to be cut.
</P>
<P>
The official said the international portion of revenue dropped
from 1995's 43.5 percent to 39 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam Airlines suffered an estimated loss of about 50 billion
Vietnamese dong (about 4.5 million U.S. dollars) last year. The
loss is expected to be higher this year.
</P>
<P>
International air cargo also dropped by eight percent compared
with the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
