<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Help in Injectable Contraceptives Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
cooperate with private medical practitioners in expanding the use
of injectable contraceptives, said an official handout received
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Health and Family Welfare Minister Salahuddin Yusuf said in an
address at a meeting here recently that the prevalence rate of
contraceptives increased from 8 percent in 1975 to over 49 percent
in 1997 while the use of modern methods also grew significantly
from 5 percent in 1975 to 42 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The minister hoped that departments concerned would promote the
modern methods in an effort to further improve the quality of life
of the less privileged people in this country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's population now stands at 127 million and the
population growth rate has fallen to 1.75 percent from 1.81
percent in 1995 thanks to family planning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
