<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Proposes Unconditional Diplomatic Ties with Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
has proposed establishing diplomatic ties between Yugoslavia and
Bosnia immediately and unconditionally, the Oslobodenje daily
circulated in Sarajevo reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Milosevic's proposal had been delivered
Monday by Milorad Dodik, the prime minister of the Serb Republic
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, to Alija Izetbegovic, the chairman of the
Bosnian Presidency.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, Yugoslavia "respects the sovereignty and
the integrity of Bosnia-Herzegovina" while "Bosnia-Herzegovina
respects Yugoslavia's right of inheritance."
</P>
<P>
Both countries should set up diplomatic relations and exchange
ambassadors "immediately and unconditionally," and agree to solve
between themselves the issue of ownership of assets left over from
the breakup of the former Yugoslavia "in accordance with the
international law," the proposal added.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Izetbegovic's office on Wednesday evening
said Bosnia was in contact with Yugoslavia on establishing
diplomatic ties. But a final decision would be made by relevant
state organs of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Dayton peace accord which ended the 1992-95 civil war in
Bosnia calls for mutual recognition and the establishment of
diplomatic ties among the countries founded following the breakup
of the former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Reiterates Commitment to Relations With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- India has reiterated its
commitment to developing good-neighborly relations with China.
</P>
<P>
In its first official response to strong Chinese reaction to
Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes' repeated anti-China
remarks in recent days, an Indian External Affairs Ministry
spokesman in a written statement issued here later Wednesday
evening said India would continue the process of normalizing ties
with China and develop a friendly, cooperative and mutually
beneficial relationship with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Fernandes in his lecture here on May 3 called China "India's
potential threat number one." A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman
on May 5 dismissed his anti-China remarks as "groundless" and
"ridiculous and not worthy of refutation."
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman said eliminating differences and promoting
understanding would contribute to the development of
good-neighborly relations between India and China, two of the
world's largest and most populous countries, and would also
contribute to the promotion of regional and international peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
In recent years there has been steady improvement in Indo-China
relations with both sides agreeing to build a constructive and
cooperative relationship oriented toward the 21st century, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the five principles of peaceful coexistence,
jointly enunciated by India and China, are of continuing relevance
to the development of inter-state relations," he said. "We see our
relationship as one in which the two sides would be responsive to
each other's concerns." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
