<HEADLINE> Ukraine, U.S. Sign Accord on Nuclear Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and the United States signed an
agreement on cooperation in the peaceful use of nuclear energy
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the U.S. government will provide Ukraine
with about 30 million U.S. dollars to help the country modernize
its nuclear fuels sector.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Ukrainian Foreign Minister Boris
Tarasyuk and U.S. Ambassador to Ukraine Stephen Pifer.
</P>
<P>
Tarasyuk told the press after the signing ceremony that the
agreement had laid a foundation for furthering the strategic
partnership between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the signing of the agreement marked the start of
preparations for the country's independent manufacturing of
nuclear fuels.
</P>
<P>
It was also an important step on the way to a smooth shutdown
of the Chernobyl nuclear power station, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the agreement's importance in ensuring nuclear
security, Ambassador Pifer said U.S. technology would help Ukraine
better use its nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. companies, he said, were interested in joining
efforts to build two power generating units for the Rovno and
Khmelnicky nuclear stations as future replacements to the
Chernobyl station.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was initialed by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on her March 6 visit to Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
