<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Will Continue to Push Japan for Economic Solutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States will continue
to encourage Japan to make a greater effort to resolve its economic
problems in order to enhance global economic growth, a Clinton
administration official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told a press briefing that
he expected Japan's problems to be a central part of the economic
discussions at meetings of finance officials this weekend in
London and next week when U.S. President Bill Clinton and leaders
of major industrial countries gather for their annual economic
summit.
</P>
<P>
"Among industrialized nations, the focus will be on Japan more
than anything else," he said commenting on upcoming meetings of
the G-7, which groups the U.S., Japan, Germany, France, Britain,
Canada and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Finance and foreign ministers of G-7 nations will meet Friday
in London and will be joined on Saturday by officials from Russia
as they prepare the agenda for the May 15-17 economic summit in
Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
In an interview earlier this week, President Clinton said he
would meet with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and
wanted "an extended period" with him to review economic concerns.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration is worried that Japan is slipping into
a recession and if it does not act more forcefully the weakness in
the world's second-largest economy could stir up the Asian
financial crisis and threaten other regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government last month released details of a 127
billion U.S. dollar package designed to use temporary tax cuts and
increased spending on public works projects to jump-start the
country's weakened economy.
</P>
<P>
But the administration has repeatedly warned that the stimulus
package is not enough unless it is accompanied by major reforms of
Japan's ailing banking system and further moves to deregulate the
economy with an aim toward lowering trade barriers that keep U.S.
and other foreign goods out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Rubin indicated that finance ministers and central bank
governors had an extended discussion of Japan's problems last
month in Washington during the spring meetings of the
International Monetary Fund; the London meeting will be a review
of developments since then.
</P>
<P>
He said the upcoming meetings were designed to prepare the
agenda for Clinton and the other heads of state for talks on the
global economy, the Asian crisis and other issues, such as the
progress being made by 11 European nations toward implementing a
single currency and the economic development in Africa, one of
Clinton's global priorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambia not to Compromise on Copper Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- It seems that Zambia will not
compromise in the foreseeable future on the privatization of its
copper mines as Mines Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye has
slammed any actions against his government's will.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Kitwe, capital of Zambia's Copperbelt Province
Tuesday, he said the Zambian government condemned ultimatums and
veiled threats being issued by local and international forces
over the privatization of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
The minister described the actions as "unhelpful" to a quick
conclusion of the sale of the remaining ZCCM mines.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process is in danger of being hijacked by
foreigners who will dictate which mines to privatize, when, to
whom and for how much, he said.
</P>
<P>
The mines minister said that Zambia is being subjected to
unacceptable arm twisting methods, bribery and blackmail over the
sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines, two biggest divisions in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Zambia discontinued the negotiations last month with Kafue
Consortium on the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines, which make up
65 percent of the ZCCM assets.
</P>
<P>
Due to falling copper prices in the international market,
Falconbridge Mining Company of Canada pulled out of the project
of Konkola Mine in March this year and two months earlier,
another Canadian firm withdrew its bid for Chambishi mine just
before signing the sale transaction agreements, citing the same
reason.
</P>
<P>
Kafue Consortium also called for renegotiations over the price
of the two biggest mines just before enterning into a final
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The consortium had reportedly agreed to buy the mines at 400
million U.S. Dollars but later pegged its bid price at 250
million Dollars and this was turned down by Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC), which has 10
percent share-holding in the Kafue Consortium claimed that the
main reason for the failure of the negotiations was because the
Zambian government was more concerned with the purchase price
than long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
CDC Chief Executive Roy Reynold said both the government and
the ZCCM did not appreciate the long-term investment of one
billion U.S. Dollars the consortium was willing to pump in to
revitalize the two mines.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba declared that Nchanga and
Nkana will not be sold off at give-away prices.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's negotiating team leader Francis Kaunda attributed the
collapse to "bad faith and dictatorial terms" by Kafue
Consortium.
</P>
<P>
He charged that initially the consortium had agreed to assume
35 million of ZCCM's 75 million Dollar debt stock upon
acquisition of the mines but it later back-tracked.
</P>
<P>
Besides reducing its cash offer, the Kafue Consortium included
other mining assets as part of the package, Kaunda said.
</P>
<P>
It also demanded a seven-year 100 percent exemption on mineral
royalties as well as a five-year exemption for excise duty and
import duty on fuels.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the lower copper prices could be one of the
main concerns to investors in the mining sector.
</P>
<P>
Another reason could be ZCCM's 800 million Dollars debt.
</P>
<P>
The Kafue Consortium, which comprises Avmin (South Africa),
Noranda (Canada), Phelps Dodge (USA) and the Commonwealth
Development Corporation (UK), won the bid for the two mines in
1997 after the Zambian government went through a protracted
process to pick the best buyer of the two divisions.
</P>
<P>
The Mine-workers Union of Zambia (MUZ) said failure of the
negotiations will delay the envisaged economic boom on the
Copperbelt.
</P>
<P>
"We are very disappointed because we hoped the earlier
privatization of the two divisions will result in the economy
picking up especially on the Copperbelt," said MUZ President Paul
Kafumbe.
</P>
<P>
Many businesses on the Copperbelt depend on the mines and the
failure of the talks meant that the economic environment will not
improve soon.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the talks have also thrown into disarray the
union's plans to negotiate improved working conditions with the
new owners.
</P>
<P>
Economics Association of Zambia (EAZ) Chairman Moses Banda
said that the bundling of the ZCCM assets in packages exposes the
country to the whims of the bidders, who form consortiums
reducing Zambia's bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
Because of copper price falls and outdated equipment, lack of
investment and mismanagement, annual copper output of the country
has decreased gradually to about 300,000 tons in recent years
from its peak 750,000 tons in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investment, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
