<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Governor Outlines Reform Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's newly-appointed central
bank Governor Chatumongol Sonakul has committed himself to
reducing foreign debts and easing the cash squeeze for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol hinted that interest rates would remain high as
they are the best defense against national debts and liquidity
crisis, the Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign debts currently stand at 90 billion U.S.
dollars, said Chatumongol, who was appointed the central bank
governor on Wednesday to replace Chaiyawat Wilbulswasdi.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat was blamed for being incompetent in handling the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said that if the baht remains at the current level
of around 38 to the dollar, there will be less pressure on the
central bank to increase interest rates.
</P>
<P>
He said he is committed to reforming the central bank but would
not change the short-term policies.
</P>
<P>
One of the tasks, he said, is to reduce speculative short-term
capital inflow and encourage productive long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the capital outflows stem from interest payments on
financial institutions' revolving credit and foreign speculative
investment. The figure had reached 4 billion U.S. dollars," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Excessive consumption, especially of imports, has to be reduced
as higher inflation is expected in the next few months, making it
difficult for the central bank to lower interest rates,
Chatumongol said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the government's role in the reform of the bank,
Chatumongol said his close ties with the government does not mean
that there would be political meddling in his work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
