<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Changes Capital's Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev signed a document Wednesday changing the name of the
country's capital Akmola to Astana, the natonal television
reported.
</P>
<P>
The president said the decision was made with wishes from
different social circles and at the request of executive and
representative organs in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The name of a national capital's name should project a positive
image and meaning, he said, but Akmola means "white tomb" in
Kazakh, and some news media have been defining the city in this
way, and that creates a very negative image, he added.
</P>
<P>
The new name, Astana, means "capital" in Kazakh, the president
said, adding that the state of Akmola will retain its original
name.
</P>
<P>
Astana, 1,300 kilometers north of the former capital Alma Ata,
covers 200 square kilometers with a population of 300,000. It
became the new capital on December 10, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
