<HEADLINE> Preparations for US-China Summit in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for the U.S.-China
summit are now in full swing as both sides are planning closer
cooperation in various fields, a senior U.S. official said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of Commerce for International Trade David Aaron
said in a luncheon briefing sponsored by Asia Society that "Many
quarters of the Administration are forging ahead with what will be
important contributions to the summit and future relations
overall."
</P>
<P>
He made the speech following a visit last month to China where
he discussed the trade issues with Chinese officials, preparing the
ground for President Bill Clinton's trip to the People's Republic
in late June.
</P>
<P>
The strategic summit, the second of its kind in less than a
year, will further push forward the overall relationship between
the United States and China, David believed.
</P>
<P>
"We at Commerce are actively mapping out a blueprint to advance
commercial engagement," he said, figuring out project finance,
standards,testing and certification, commercial law and other
areas for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We also are working on broader aviation, housing,
infrastructure, and insurance initiatives, all of which have
important implications for the summit," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Beijing and Shanghai, David witnessed nearly
200 million U.S. dollars in signings, including more than 170
million dollars in contracts for U.S. power generation,
information technologies, and air conditioning equipment, and more
than 25 million dollars in investments for a U.S-Shanghai based
food venture.
</P>
<P>
"China's leaders are determined to achieve better relations
with the United States and a positive summit," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged China to further open its market to U.S. products and
services so as to narrow the huge trade imbalance between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that we are making progress. However, we need to
do more on matters dealing with industrial and agricultural
tariffs, distribution, professional, financial, and
telecommunications services," he said.
</P>
<P>
David disclosed that several dozen meetings are scheduled to be
held between the two countries over the next year in continued
effort to bridge differences and further cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshevsky also visited China last month in
preparation for President Clinton's China trip. Among other
issues, China's access to the World Trade Organization (WTO) was
high in their talks with Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
They both recognized that progress has been made by China on
the matter, but they insisted there is still a long way to go
toward China's full WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
However, Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing, Speaking Wednesday at
an international trade conference here, said that after 11 years
of economic reform and efforts to gain access to the WTO,
including five time reduction of tariff, "China really has already
lived up to the conditions for entering that world trading body."
</P>
<P>
"We can only join ( WTO) as what we are, that is, as a developing
member of the international community. And of course, once inside,
we'll perform our obligations," Ambassador Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that China is ready to buy more things from the
U.S. in order to narrow the trade deficit between the two
countries. "However, we also hope that your country will further
relax its export controls so that we can buy some of your more
expensive things," he replied to an American participant.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed sanctions against China in 1989. Its
high-tech exports to China have since been strictly restricted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
