<HEADLINE> Italy, U.S. Open on Military Option for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton and visiting Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said on
Wednesday the use of troops was an option to prevent ethnic war in
the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference following their meeting,
Clinton said he was ready to turn up pressure on Yugoslavia if it
continued to block a search for a peaceful solution to rising
violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we can rule out any options, because we don't
want another Bosnia to happen," Clinton said when asked about the
possibility of sending troops to the region.
</P>
<P>
"Neither, however, do we want to get in a position where Italy
has to send troops to every one of its neighboring countries and
the United States has to send troops every time there's a dispute
in that part of the world," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said solving the problem would require finding a way to
grant the "legitimate aspirations" of ethnic-Albanian Kosovo
residents for more autonomy while honoring Serbian desires not to
give up a big part of their country.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he agreed with Clinton. "We didn't rule out any
solution. We are just making an effort to arrive at a peaceful
solution," said the Italian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said troops conceivably could be used to guard against
cross-border arms smuggling. "Even this option is dangerous,
because in some ways, whenever you send troops, you send...
potential hostages to the situation."
</P>
<P>
He said he and Clinton had also discussed the possibility of
recovery assistance for civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Also at the press conference, the two leaders expressed their
satisfaction with the Italy-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"For more than 50 years, Italy has been among our closest
allies," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"As we celebrate all the ties that bind us, we are looking
ahead to the next 50 years, to an even stronger and more vibrant
partnership, which will shape a brighter future for all our
people," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his regrets about the the Marine jet accident that
killed 20 skiers in the Italian Alps in February.
</P>
<P>
Fighting back tears in his eyes, Clinton responded to a
question, "I regret terribly what happened, and I cannot bring
back the people who perished."
</P>
<P>
"But I will do my best to make sure that we behave in a
completely honorable way and a way that is completely consistent
with the commitments we have made."
</P>
<P>
Prodi referred to relations as being in a "magic moment". He
said: "We have no points of disagreements.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is only to build up strong relations and to bring
them into the future in a moment that is very favorable to that,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Prodi commended Clinton over the economic situation in the
U.S., saying it was very rare to see eight years of continuous
growth without inflation, but with decreasing unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"And I think the Euro may give us the same possibility for
Europe," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Both Clinton and Prodi agreed that new negotiations should be
launched for a broader and stronger partnership between Europe and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Europe needs a new set of relations between Europe and the
United States, because these new events need a new organization of
our relations. So I'm very favorable to the proposal of a
trans-Atlantic new set of economic and political relations," Prodi
affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "What I want is a strong, united Europe that is
our partner in dealing with the challenges and in seizing the
opportunities to the 21st century world."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Clinton noted that U.S. personnel from the
Aviano air base were assisting in rescue efforts after this week's
storms in southern Italy and expressed thanks to Italians for
their "hospitality toward United States forces working to preserve
peace in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"That was only the beginning of a relationship that has now
flourished for centuries bringing us together in new ways
generation after generation," Clinton said at a welcoming ceremony
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
In his own remarks, from a reviewing stand on the South Lawn,
Prodi called their two nations "two citizens of the next
millennium bound by common values".
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he wanted to pursue a "vast sphere of free trade"
between the U.S. and Europe "not only to best utilize our energy
and to strengthen as much as possible our political and economic
ties but also as a common contribution to the global trade
liberalization." 
</P>
</TEXT>
