<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Scientists Record Largest Explosion in Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Astronomers from NASA said
Wednesday that they have recorded the largest explosion, called
a GRB971214 gamma-ray burst, in the universe.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the NASA headquarters here,
astronomers from several teams said GRB971214 gamma-ray burst may
be the largest energy release since the ``Big Bang'' which caused
the birth of our universe, hurling out more than 100 times the
energy the sun will emit during its entire 10-billion-year
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, located about 12 billion light years away in the
constellation Ursa Major, has two particular features. One is its
huge energy, and the other is its long distance. Therefore the
finding is a great accomplishment in astronomy.
</P>
<P>
The Gamma ray bursts were first detected on December 14, 1997,
by the Italian and Dutch BeppoSAX satellite and NASA's Compton
Gamma Ray Observatory satellite.
</P>
<P>
Gamma-ray bursts are mysterious flashes of high-energy
radiation that appear from random directions in space and
typically last a few seconds. They were first discovered by U.S.
Air Force Vela satellites in the 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
