<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Predicts Decline in Venezuela's Oil Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's oil revenue this year
will drop by some 3 billion U.S. dollars when the crude price
averages between 13-13.5 dollars per barrel, a Venezuelan expert
predicted.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the "El Globo" journal, analyst Felix
Rossi Guerrero said he did not believe the oil price would soar up
to 15 dollars per barrel soon.
</P>
<P>
The recovery of oil prices in the international market would be
possible only if both members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) and independent oil producers agreed to
reduce their production by 500,000 barrels per day, Guerrero said.
</P>
<P>
Crude prices fell by 40 percent from October to mid-March as a
result of weak demand in cash-strapped Asian countries, a
10-percent rise in OPEC's 1998 production ceiling, a mild northern
hemisphere winter and increased Iraqi exports.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, Mexico and Saudi Arabia signed an agreement in March
to reduce their production by 200,000 and 300,000 barrels per day
respectively to cope with the outbreak of an oil pricing crisis.
</P>
<P>
In March, Venezuela saw its crude basket go down to almost 10
dollars per barrel and now it has recovered to around 12 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Noting that certain stability and a slight price recovery will
be observed in the coming months, Guerrero added that the prices
would stay around 13 dollars per barrel, compared with 16.32
dollars during the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
