<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Army Deserters Hired by Security Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Defense Ministry which
is attempting to get back some 19,000 army deserters through a
five-day amnesty ending May 10, has discovered that most of them
have been employed by security firms.
</P>
<P>
These private institutions have been warned not to recruit the
deserters but to hand them over to the nearest police station, the
official newspaper News Daily quoted military sources as saying
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's law, which the government hopes to strictly
enforce after the amnesty deadline, harboring a deserter, abetting
such desertion and employing deserters are punishable offenses.
</P>
<P>
In addition to private security firms, police believe, night
clubs and casinos also hire army deserters as strongarm men.
</P>
<P>
The government Monday declared a general amnesty period from
May 5 to 10 to give military deserters an opportunity to rejoin
the security forces.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that soon after the amnesty deadline raids will
be conducted on places where deserters are believed to be
employed and that the employers will also be arrested together
with the deserters.
</P>
<P>
Deserters who surrender before the deadline will not be
punished under the amnesty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
