<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference Stresses Importance of Girls' Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- About 500 leaders and experts from
28 countries representing governments, civil societies, businesses,
religions and the media gathered here on Wednesday to stress the
urgent need to improve education for girls throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
"Two of three children who do not finish primary school are
girls, despite the direct benefit of girls' education to economies
and family health," said a conference news release entitled
"Education of girls is a development imperative."
</P>
<P>
According to a 1997 Human Development Report of the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP), there are about 110 million
children in the primary school-going group and another 275 million
children at secondary school level who are out of school in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
A 1998 UNDP report noted that almost one billion adults
worldwide are not literate and more than half of them are women.
</P>
<P>
Three out of every five of the 400 million illiterates in South
Asia are women and almost half of adult women in Africa are
illiterate. In India, three in every five girls drop out of school
before they finish the primary school course.
</P>
<P>
In Sub-Sahara Africa and in West Asia the gender gap in primary
school enrollment is worst. In Benin, there are 36 percent less
girls enrolling in primary school than boys; in Yemen, 34 percent;
in Chad, 28 percent and in Guinea-Bissau 26 percent. On average,
sub-Saharan primary schools see only 68 girls enrolling for every
100 boys.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is sponsored by the United States
Agency for International Development (USAID), the Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) and the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) as well as other organizations in the effort to mobilize
leaders from public, private and nonprofit sectors to advance
girls' education.
</P>
<P>
A USAID administrator, Brian Atwood, stressed the importance
for girls' education to economic development. "If countries want
to achieve economic and social development, no investment has a
higher pay-off than educating girls.
</P>
<P>
"Educating girls contributes to economic growth, leads to
better cared-for families and to stronger democracies."
</P>
<P>
Enrique Iglesias, President of IDB, said: "The education of
girls is a key factor for improving social equity and reducing
poverty."
</P>
<P>
And UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said education for
girls was the key to health and nutrition of populations, to
overall improvements in the standards of living, to better culture
and to greater involvement and gender balance in decision-making
at all levels of society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
