<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Cultural Forum Begins in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from eight Latin
American countries and Spain gathered in a forum here Wednesday to
seek ways to develop Latin-American cultures.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian Education Minister Pablo Thalassinos inaugurated the
second Congress of National Culture and Identity Construction in
Latin America. The forum was attended by delegates from Bolivia,
Chile, Colombia, Cuba, Ecuador, Peru, Venezuela, Panama and Spain.
</P>
<P>
"This congress aims to join reflections and alternatives of
state-nation issues as well as those of identity categories and
national culture," Thalassinos said.
</P>
<P>
He called for more active participation in efforts to build
democratic and efficient states that promote inter-cultural
dialogue among various communities and ethnic groups in the region.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will discuss ways to promote national cultures as
argumentative expressions of the work and aspirations of
indigenous peoples, Afro-Americans, caucasians and mestizos
living in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
They will also analyze new examples of national cultures and
identities in the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
The first culture congress, held in Quito, capital of Ecuador,
in July 1997, established the base for new dialogue on culture,
development and integration in Latin America, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The Panama meeting is expected to build an instrumental
framework for dialogue between official and non-governmental
institutions on the construction of a Latin-American identity,
they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
