<HEADLINE> Thai Drivers to Get "Smart" Driving Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai drivers may have "smart"
driving licenses in the near future which will help them register
vehicles and enforce traffic regulations.
</P>
<P>
The new driving license with a "smart card" feature will give
police quick access to the holder's record of traffic violations
using information stored in microchips in the card, the Transport
and Communication Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The license, with the size of a bank ATM card, would also
benefit holders by helping them bypass lengthy paperwork
procedures when they register their vehicles at motor vehicle
offices or pay fines.
</P>
<P>
An official in the ministry was quoted by the newspaper Bangkok
Post Thursday as saying the use of smart licenses would upgrade
Thailand's vehicle registration system to Western standards.
</P>
<P>
It would also help solve the problem of driving license
forgery, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Land Transportation Department, which is in charge of
issuing the new license, would allow private companies to produce
the cards through concession in return for fees to be collected
from holders at a certain rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Store For Foreigners Now Open To All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Friendship Store on the eastern
edge of Beijing's downtown area used to be open only to
foreigners, but it's been refurbished and is open to everyone now.
</P>
<P>
The store was set up in the 1960s when there was a serious
shortage of certain goods in China, to make life more convenient
for foreigners who were working here. As recently as the late 80s,
guards at the front door of the three-story Soviet-style building
would ask to see the foreign passport of anyone wanting to enter
who appeared to be Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In the past, foreigners paid for goods that were in short
supply by using foreign currency certificates, known
as 'FEC'. Their face value was the same as the renminbi (RMB), but
they sold for 30 to 80 percent more on the black market, and could
then be used by Chinese to buy some hard-to-get goods.
</P>
<P>
The store was quite prominent in those days because many VIPs
like presidents and premiers had visited it. And the average
foreign tourist, guidebook in hand, would find his or her way to
the store to buy essentials that the ordinary Chinese could not
afford.
</P>
<P>
But, with the reforms and opening-up and the economic boom,
China said good-by to the shortage of goods -- and to this system
of privilege. Foreigners in Beijing now do their shopping in any
store they choose, and at the same time, Chinese can easily buy
many goods almost anywhere that could previously only be bought by
foreigners in the old Friendship Store.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the store was merged with Xidan Market, one of
Beijing's biggest general department stores, and was closed
recently for redecoration. It opened for business 6 days ago.
</P>
<P>
You can see the change when the store's spokesman, Li Xiujun,
says, "What we should do is to change the store's image in an
all-round way, and we have to make more adjustments and respond to
the market economy."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
