<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay Foreign Trade Deficit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Uruguayan trade deficit
reached 105 million U.S. dollars in January, the central bank said
in a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit resulted from 285 million dollars in imports which
surpassed the 180 million dollars in exports.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period last year, exports decreased
three percent and imports grew only 0.7 percent last January,
according to the central bank report.
</P>
<P>
The export of traditional products such as wool, rice and
woolen fabrics suffered most from the decline.
</P>
<P>
The import of consumer goods registered a major increase, while
the purchase of capital goods went down.
</P>
<P>
The major buyer of Uruguayan products is the southern common
market (Mercosur), which bought 52.4 percent of the total export
products.
</P>
<P>
Israel is the fourth largest market for Uruguayan products
after the United States.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Uruguayan exports reached a record high of 2.73
billion dollars, an increase of 13.9 percent compared with that of
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in 1997 soared to 3.47 billion dollars, 11.8 percent
more than that in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
