<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba, Mexico Spend More Money on Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba has the largest education
budget in Latin-America followed by Mexico, a recent survey on
basic education undertaken by the United Nations revealed here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that Cuba invests 10.3 percent of it's Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) in the education sector, followed by Mexico
with 5.2 percent and Panama with 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation's most recent survey indicates that Cuba had
13 pupils per teacher in 1997 at an elementary education level,
while Paraguay had 18, the Dominican Republic had 23, Mexico and
Peru registered 28.
</P>
<P>
In regards to high school levels, Paraguay holds first place in
the number of students per teacher with a figure of nine, followed
by Cuba and Uruguay with 10, Costa Rica with 14 and Mexico with 16.
</P>
<P>
The education expenditure in other Latin-American nations is as
follows: Ecuador with 4.5 percent, Brazil with 4.5 percent and
Costa Rica with 4.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
