<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drive Against Drugs in China Gets Off to Good Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China's anti-drug campaign has got
off to a very good start this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, Chinese police cracked 22,000
drug-related cases, 6 percent up from the same period of
1997, today's China Daily quoted Yang Fengrui, vice director of
the Office of the National Narcotics Control Commission, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
About 28,000 people involved in these cases were caught, 7.6
percent up compared with the same period of last year, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months, police confiscated 1.6 tons of
heroin, 58.6 percent up, and 0.31 tons of opium, 98.7 percent up.
</P>
<P>
They also confiscated 0.5 tons of marijuana, 17.9 kilograms of
amphetamines and 43.2 tons of chemicals which can easily be used
to manufacture drugs, according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
Yang warned that China's fight against drugs still faces an
uphill task.
</P>
<P>
The "Golden Triangle" area bordering southwest China's Yunnan
Province, where annual production of opium has reached 2,500 tons,
causes a great deal of harm to China, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang, China had 540,000 registed drug addicts by
the end of 1997, more than 80 percent of whom are young
people. Drug abuse has spread to 1,920 Chinese cities and
counties, he added.
</P>
<P>
Education is urgently needed on the harm caused by drugs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A special nationwide anti-drug campaign launched last year
achieved the best results in the drug control in recent years, Yang
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 2,500 drug rings were smashed and 9,963 people taken
into custody. Both figures were 70 percent up on 1996,
according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
Police confiscated a record 5.477 tons of heroin last year.
</P>
<P>
Over 180,000 addicts received forced treatment in compulsory
rehabilitation centers last year, 50,000 more than in 1996, Yang
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Chinese government attaches great importance to
drug control and is determined to step up efforts to fight drugs.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
