<HEADLINE> Unemployment in NZ Reaches Four-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in New
Zealand reached 7.1 percent in the first quarter this year, the
highest level in almost four years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said in a media release received on
Thursday that the total jobless figure is estimated at 129,000 at
the end of March, up 7,000 on the previous quarter and 13,000 more
 than one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister Peter McCardle blamed the rise on the Asian
 financial crisis and the drought in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"The widely forecast strengthening of economic and related
employment growth has been delayed," he noted.
</P>
<P>
But he believed that the impending tax cuts, the lower New
Zealand dollar, the expected easing of interest rates and some
other factors should facilitate strong economic growth later this
year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that New Zealand's unemployment rate is below
the average of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development countries.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists have predicted that unemployment could
 peak at 8 percent by the middle of next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
