<HEADLINE> New Zealand Finds New Gasfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The eastern part of New Zealand's

North Island could become the country's another major gasfield as
a
test well there has shown "commercial success," the Wellington
newspaper The Dominion reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Enerco company has drilled its first test well, which
produced 325,000 cubic meters of gas a day. But it believed that
the
potential could reach 2 million cubic meters a day.
</P>
<P>
Enerco is now drilling the second well, which the company said
is
showing signs of being at least as good as the first one.
</P>
<P>
After the output is ascertained, Enerco will invest 60 million
dollars (33 million U.S. dollars) to build a pipeline linking the

field near the town of Wairoa, 450 km north of Wellington, to
Napier,
118 km south of Wairoa. The gas will supply the Hawke's Bay
region.
</P>
<P>
The Wairoa will be the second largest gasfield in New Zealand
after Taranaki in eastern North Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
