<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 Killed by Landslides in Southern Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 25 people were killed and more
than 70 others were feared buried alive Wednesday when torrents of
mud and debris roared through densely populated areas in southern
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Two days of incessant rain caused local streams to burst with a
ferocious intensity, unleashing mud, debris and water that
engulfed hundreds of homes in the affected areas, the Italian news
media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Competent authorities have called out military helicopters,
thousands of fire-fighters, soldiers and emergency workers to the
affected areas to search for survivors.
</P>
<P>
The Government has declared a state of emergency, promising 29
million U.S. dollars in immediate aid to the victims.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano rushed to the
affected areas later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports quoted the Italian civil protection agency
as saying that at 1,800 people were left homeless throughout the
affected areas ranging between Naples and Salerno.
</P>
<P>
Mud and debris have also covered railroad tracks and roads,
bringing the distribution of relief supplies to a standstill.
Power and telephone lines were cut off in many parts of the
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rain in the affected areas stopped by mid-day
Wednesday and meteorologists said the weather would continue to
improve.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Italy's civil protection agency, Andrea Todisco, told
the local media that many homes in the affected areas had been
illegally built too close to rivers or in areas prone to
landslides. As a result, the damage was aggravated, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
