<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Urged to Be Deferred in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Commission on Elections has been
urged to suspend elections in most parts of Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, because of "massive anomalies" in voter registration,
the Philippine Star Thursday reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said Nur Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region
in Muslim Mindanao and chairman of the Southern Philippines
Council for Peace and Development, Wednesday visited the poll body
in Manila to persuade it to postpone the polls in certain areas in
Mindanao "until anomalies in the registration lists are
corrected."
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the results of the coming elections will not reflect
the real voice of the people," Misuari said, denouncing reported
massive padding of voters' lists.
</P>
<P>
"The registration really needs to be rehashed after this
election. Where else can you see registered names belonging to
newborn babies, every child in the family, maybe even the dogs and
chickens?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Misuari's call came on the heels of a warning from the
Commission on Elections that there could be a failure of elections
in Mindanao. He did not identify the areas in Mindanao where there
are padded voters' lists being probed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believed that mudslinging, cheating, fraud and
violence will occur in next week's elections, especially in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Misuari is the chief of the Moro National Liberation Front
which signed a final peace agreement with the government in 1996
after 24 years of war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
