<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former East German Swimmer Says She was Doped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A former East German swimmer told a
court on Wednesday she had been given performance-enhancing drugs
from the age of 14.
</P>
<P>
Birgit-Heike Matz said she was ordered to take "little blue
pills", which according to the prosecutors' charges contained the
banned steroid oral-turinabol.
</P>
<P>
From 1973 to 1978, Matz was in the training group of Rolf
Glaeser -- one of six officials on trial for allegedly causing
bodily harm to female swimmers by giving them drugs.
</P>
<P>
From 1978 until the end of her career in 1979, Matz, whose best
result was a third place in the European junior championships,
trained under the orders of another of the officials on trial,
Dieter Krause.
</P>
<P>
The six on trial -- four swimming coaches and two doctors --
are accused of giving 19 female swimmers steroids between 1975 and
1989.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, coaches Glaeser, Krause, Volker Frischke, Dieter
Lindemann and doctors Dieter Binus and Bernd Pansold, could face
several years in jail.
</P>
<P>
The trial, the first to put East Germany's doping policy under
examination, is scheduled to last until at least in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
