<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Develops High-Efficiency Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Scores of high-efficiency
agricultural bases with a total area of 66,000 ha have been
established in Henan Province, central China.
</P>
<P>
At the bases, farmers have interplanted crops with
vegetables. The fields are covered with glass or plastic sheets.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the multiple crop index has increased from 174
percent to 250 percent.
</P>
<P>
In winter, farmers at the bases grow vegetables or fruit, which
could only be seen in summer or autumn before. They have also
imported quality vegetable species from the United States,
Israel and the Netherlands. The prices of these vegetables are a
dozen times higher than those for other species.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some service companies have been set up to collect
farm produce from individual growers and sell them in cities.
</P>
<P>
Provincial statistics show that 3,490 such companies had been
set up in Henan by the end of last year, which have connections
with 8.24 million farm households, accounting for 30 percent of
the province's total.
</P>
<P>
In this way, farmers no long worry about how to transport and
sell their products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Attack Mortality Falls in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Mortality of heart attack patients
has fallen by 10 percent since 1995, the American health Quality
Association reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was achieved as a result of effective cooperation between
the federal government and private sector health care quality
experts, the association said in a press report.
</P>
<P>
It has collected data from over 250,000 medical records in four
pilot states - Alabama, Connecticut, Iowa and Wisconsin with the
latest data showing a 10 percent decrease in mortality since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The association works collaboratively with health care
practitioners, health plans and hospitals, to analyze health care
patterns, identify opportunities for improvement and interpret and
share information about current science and best practices with
physicians and hospitals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Children Recognize bias on TV: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 6 (Xinhua) -- American children think it is
important to see their own race on television -- and
African-American, Asian and Latino children are more likely to
think so, according to a latest study.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Wednesday by Children Now, a national
children's advocacy group based in Okland, California, raises
questions about how the media's portrayal of different ethnic
groups effects children perceptions of reality and of themselves.
</P>
<P>
According to the organization, the most powerful finding of the
research is how clearly and how early children see inequity in the
portrayal of races in the media. The study on media images of race
and class focuses on the opinions of 1,200 children across the
country who were polled and others who were invited to participate
in focus groups in four cities earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
There are very different viewing patterns among kids of
different races. Talk shows, for instance, fall into the
top-viewing category for African-American and Latino children, but
listed as the least likely to be watched by white and Asian
children.
</P>
<P>
African-American children strongly feel that the entertainment
media represents their race more fairly than the news media, while
Asian children feel the opposite, slightly favoring the news media
with 36 percent to 28 percent. White and Latino children were
split between the two.
</P>
<P>
Minority children primarily chose African-Americans as those
they admire on TV and white children primarily chose white
television figures as their favorite. "Because they are funny" was
the primary reason for admiring the figures.
</P>
<P>
A 1995 survey also conducted by Children Now found that
American children were widely exposed to the media. Fifty-eight of
children watch two or more hours of television a day. Sixty-six of
them live in a household with three or more television sets and 54
percent have a TV set in their own room. According to that survey,
most children believe that kids their age are influenced by the
entertainment media. Although 73 percent of kids think television
is mostly entertainment, 82 percent say television shows should
help teach kids right from wrong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China today
issued the market exchange rates in RMB yuan against three major
currencies. The middle price of RMB against convertible currencies
is mainly based on the closing price of the preceding interbank
trading.
</P>
<P>
The designated foreign exchange trading banks will decide the
exchange rates in RMB yuan against other convertible currencies
according to the tone of the international exchange market and the
rules of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
