<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Asks U.S. to Refer Water Export to Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada asked the United States
Wednesday to agree to refer the issue of Great Lakes water export
to the International Joint Commission (IJC).
</P>
<P>
The referral of the issue to the commission was prompted by a
permit, granted to a Canadian company by the Ontario provincial
environment ministry, for the annual export of 600 million litres
of Lake Superior water to Asia until 2002.
</P>
<P>
Canada and the United State share the world's largest fresh
waterlake of Superior. The permit has angered both
environmentalists of the two countries and U.S. government
officials.
</P>
<P>
One U.S. Congressman in Michigan was reported to have asked
</P>
<P>
the U.S. State Department to investigate the matter.
</P>
<P>
"I have written Secretary of State Madeleine Albright asking
that she agree to bring this issue to the IJC," Canadian Foreign
Affair Minister Lloyd Axworthy was quoted as saying by a
government news release.
</P>
<P>
The IJC is an independent binational organization set up under
the Canada-U.S. Boundary Waters Treaty of 1909. Its central role
is to prevent and resolve disputes and to examine issues
concerning waters that cross or lie on the border.
</P>
<P>
The company that made a splash with lake water export plans has
said that it is willing to surrender the permit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
