<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street fell
Wednesday, with the Dow Jones industrial average falling 92.92
points to 9,054.65.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also surrendered early gains amid some
indications that the Asian financial crisis is far from resolved.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, stocks tumbled 4.7 percent amid a third day.
Elsewhere in the region, stocks fell 2.3 percent in Tokyo and 3.9
percent in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
U.S. shares opened higher, however, amid news that Daimler-Benz
might acquire Chrysler in a deal that could be worth 35 billion
U.S. dollars. Share prices of both companies soared on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The advance in the broad market quickly faded, however, as
investors refocused on the rate increase issue.
</P>
<P>
There was little reaction to a Federal Reserve report saying
economic growth continued at a "moderate to strong" pace in March
and April.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 10.75 to 1,104.90. The
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fared better, falling just
8.23 to 1,856.68.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-5 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 606.54 million shares,
higher than the modest pace of recent sessions.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 5.18 to 574.57, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.95 to 743.33.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.37 to 479.37.
</P>
