<HEADLINE> Gingrich Accuses Clinton of Pressuring Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- House Speaker Newt Gingrich
Wednesday accused the Clinton administration of pressuring Israel
on peace terms with "threats and ultimatums."
</P>
<P>
He said in a letter, to be sent to President Bill Clinton, that
Israel "should not be punished with threat and ultimatums."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has complained to
Israel's Army Radio that the United States was pressuring him into
agreeing to "certain conditions that are unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
"I don't accept dictates. We're a sovereign country," he said.
"We must decide alone what is important for our future."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said earlier that he never wanted to dictate Israel to
accept terms set by Washington.
</P>
<P>
"There's no way in the world I could impose an agreement on
them or dictate... to them even if I wished to do that," he said
at a White House news conference.
</P>
<P>
But Gingrich said the Clinton administration was using
"strong-arm tactics" to force Israel to accept its proposals on
the redeployment of the Israeli troops on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said he was increasingly concerned that the Clinton policy
favored Palestinian positions at the expense of Israel's security
needs. He called on the administration to let the people of Israel,
not Washington, decide their fate.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that genuine peace in Israel can only be
achieved through voluntary direct dialogue between the parties,
and not as a result of heavy-handed outside pressure by the United
States," he said. "Israel must be able to decide her own security
needs and set her own conditions for negotiations without facing
coercion from the U.S." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
