<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, U.S. Try to Further Strengthen Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
visiting Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi Wednesday charted a
course to strengthen cooperation between their countries for
future.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Clinton and Prodi discussed issues
ranging from the European Monetary Union and the situation in
Kosovo to fighting against international crimes.
</P>
<P>
"For more than 50 years, Italy has been among our closest
allies," Clinton told a joint press conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"As we celebrate all the ties that bind us, we are looking
ahead to the next 50 years, to an even stronger and more vibrant
partnership, which will shape a brighter future for all our
people," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his regrets about the the Marine jet accident that
killed 20 skiers in the Italian Alps in February.
</P>
<P>
Prodi expressed his satisfaction at the Italy-U.S. relations.
"We have no points of disagreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is only to build up strong relations and to bring
them into the future in a moment that is very favorable to
that," he added.
</P>
<P>
Prodi commended Clinton over the economic situation in the
U.S., saying "It's very rare to see eight years of continuous
growth without inflation, with decreasing unemployment."
</P>
<P>
Both Clinton and Prodi agreed that new negotiations should be
launched for a broader and stronger partnership between Europe
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Europe needs a new set of relations between Europe and the
United States, because these new events need a new organization
of our relations. So I'm very favorable to the proposal of a
trans-Atlantic new set of economic and political relations,"
Prodi affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "What I want is a strong, united Europe that is
our partner in dealing with the challenges and in seizing the
opportunities to the 21st century world."
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he wanted to pursue a "vast sphere of free trade"
between the U.S. and Europe "not only to best utilize our energy
and to strengthen as much as possible our political and economic
ties but also as a common contribution to the global trade
liberalization."
</P>
<P>
Prodi arrived here on Tuesday for his first official visit to
the U.S. as the prime minister of Italy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
