<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Cuba no Longer Threat to Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba does not pose threat any
longer to the United States or its neighbors, according to a new
Pentagon intelligence report issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by the Defense Intelligence Agency in
cooperation with the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and other
intelligence branches, said Cuba's armed forces had been slashed
in half to fewer than 65,000 troops since 1989 when it was Latin
America's largest military force.
</P>
<P>
"Severe resource shortages have force the FAR (Cuban
Revolutionary Armed Forces) to reduce training significantly," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that significant numbers of Cuban troops were
now used in agricultural, business and other activities.
</P>
<P>
"At present, Cuba does not pose a significant military threat
to the U.S. or to other countries in the region. Cuba has little
motivation to engage in military activity beyond defense of its
territory and political system," it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that Cuba still had the capability to
make biological weapons, but finding no evidence that the
Caribbean Island had made such weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba's biotechnology industry is one of the most advanced in
emerging countries and would be capable of producing BW
(biological weapons) agents," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
