<HEADLINE> Dutch Labor Party Leads Election: Preliminary Result </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Wim Kok's Labor
Party won the Dutch general elections Wednesday after preliminary
results showed that his party had got 46 seats from a possible
total of 150 in the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Labor got nine more seats than it did in the 1994
elections.
</P>
<P>
Second and third places in the house went to the coalition
People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and the major opposition
Christian Democratic Appeal.
</P>
<P>
The people's party got 38 seats while the Christian democrats
got 28 seats.
</P>
<P>
The third coalition Democrats 66 got 13 seats while the
ecological Green Left party got 12 seats.
</P>
<P>
The people's party gained seven more seats whereas the
Christian democrats lost six.
</P>
<P>
The biggest loss, however, was posted by the coalition
Democrats 66 that saw 11 seats drifting away. The Democrats 66
pledged prior to Wednesday's elections not to take part in the
three-party coalition if it lost half of its 24 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Green Left registered a big gain with seven more seats.
</P>
<P>
Persistent drizzle was reported to have kept almost half of the
11.7 million eligible voters at home and from casting their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
The election commission is still calculating the incoming
results and an unofficial outcome is expected to come out early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official result will be announced by the election
commission next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
