<HEADLINE> Auto Industry to Be Affected by Chrysler, Daimler Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The merger talks between Chrysler
Corp., the No. 3 auto maker of the United States, and Germany's
biggest industrial company, the maker of the Mercedes-Benz, will
reshape the auto industry, according to American auto experts.
</P>
<P>
The merger, if successful, will reportedly be the biggest U.S.
industrial merger ever.
</P>
<P>
Combining Daimler-Benz, the German luxury car maker, with the
pioneer of middle-class minivans would not only bring together
makers of two different classes of autos, but would also
significantly broaden the global reach of both companies, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler would get greater access to the European market, while
Daimler-Benz would gain a bigger foothold in the American market,
where it has been working to increase sales.
</P>
<P>
At present, the two automakers said that a deal is far from
certain.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz has increased U.S. sales 67 percent this year.
But the market share of the German automaker is just a little more
than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Chrysler sold only 17,713 vehicles outside North
America last month, more than half of that in Europe. Chrysler sold
nearly 221,000 vehicles in the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
Daimler's stock rose 6.50 U.S. dollars to 108.56 U.S. dollars
on the New York Stock Exchange Wednesday. Chrysler surged 7.31
U.S. dollars to 48.75 U.S. dollars, giving the automaker a market
value of 31.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler has 94,300 employees and a 16 percent share of new
vehicle sales this year. Only General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor
Co. sell more, with shares of 31 percent and 24 percent,
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980507.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: UN Backs Mediation for Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan said here Wednesday that the U.N.
supports the mediation by Tanzanian former president Julius
Nyerere over the Burundi crisis for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the meeting between the U.N. chief and President
Benjamin Mkapa at the State House, a senior U.N. official
disclosed that Annan also discussed with Mkapa about other
important issues related to the Great Lakes region countries.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here on Wednesday afternoon from a visit to
the northern town of Arusha, is also deeply concerned about the
rapid inflow of the Rwanda refugees into Tanzania, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks were stalled last year after the
Burundian military junta led by Pierre Buyoya said it had no
faith in Nyerere, the international mediator in the Burundi
political conflict, who is an advocate of continuing to impose
economic sanctions on the central African nation.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), have imposed sanctions on Burundi since
August of 1996 after Major Buyoya toppled a civilian government
of President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya in July of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In late March Nyerere sent his envoy Judge Mark Bomani to
Burundi for discussions with the warring parties before the
resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner after the talks at the State House,
President Mkapa expressed appreciation for Annan's recent report
to the U.N. Security Council which calls for more attention and
investment in the poorest continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is on his first official visit to Tanzania since he
came to office as the U.N. Secretary General, spoke highly of
Tanzania's role in the liberation of Southern Africa and in the
world affairs especially in its support to the U.N. affairs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said Africa is at the turning point, with the
whole continent which has witnessed less conflicts and achieved
economic progress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He praised Tanzania's efforts in hosting hundreds of thousands
of refugees in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Tanzania owes a lot to the United Nations which has
lent great support to his country. He also said African countries
need to focus on the development of infrastructure, such as
telecommunications, railways and ports.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, for example, out of 1,000 people only three has
telephones, a density much lower than countries in other
continents.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Secretary General met foreign diplomats and the
U.N. staff in Dar es Salaam, urging them to contribute more to
the U.N. process.
</P>
<P>
Annan is scheduled to conclude his two-day visit to Tanzania
Thursday morning before leaving for Bujumbura, Burundi in central
Africa.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Arusha Tuesday, Annan was encouraged by
the progress made by the International Criminal Tribunal for
Rwanda (ICTR), saying that the Tribunal has effected major
improvements in its operations and is moving ahead to fulfill its
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks were apparently to clear the air over mounting
criticism on the inefficiency of the ICTR in executing cases.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal opened its first trial only in January last year,
more than two years after its establishment in November, 1994
under a resolution by the U.N. Security Council. But only two
cases are approaching its final till now.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the former prime minister of Rwanda, Jean Kambanda,
pleaded guilty to all six charges of genocide while the first
accused, Paul Akayesu, is awaiting for judgement expected to be
delivered before the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived from Nairobi, Kenya, toured the ICTR
premises and attended a court session before departing for a game
view in the well-known Ngorongoro Crater National Park with his
wife Nane. He jokingly said he was received by elephants and a
rhinoceros of extraordinary size. 
</P>
</TEXT>
