<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Washington Meeting to Revive Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The State Department said
Wednesday that the United States hoped Israel and the Palestinians
could agree on terms for reviving the stalled Middle East peace
process when they hold talks in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful that the parties will be able to come to
agreement on the basis of the U.S. ideas which would permit the
launching of permanent status negotiations," spokesman James Foley
said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has invited Israeli and Palestinian
leaders to Washington next week for more talks following London
meetings early this week on a final peace accord if Israel accepts
U.S. proposals on a further 13.1 percent of pullback from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the White House said the talks on the Middle East
peace process were at a critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
"We're at a very critical moment where the parties have to make
a critical decision on how they want to proceed," White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
He denied that the United States was trying to dictate terms to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who complained earlier
to Israel's Army Radio that he was ready to go to Washington but
did not want to be pressured into agreeing to "certain conditions
that are unacceptable" to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the prospects for the Washington talks, McCurry
said, "I think it's unknown at this point."
</P>
<P>
He said it was conceivable that Israel would not make a final
decision on whether to attend the meeting in Washington until
Netanyahu discussed it during his regular cabinet meeting Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
